{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b9c0caee35f3ff95", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                        A Reliability Assessment of LALM Audio Judges for\n2\t                                                      Full-Duplex Voice Agents\n3\t\n4\t                                                           A. Sayyad, J. Emmons, S. Jones, T. Lin, H. Krishnan\n5\t                                                                  Salesforce Applied AI Research, eVerse team\n6\t\n7\t\n8\t                                                                                    Abstract\n9\t\n10\t                                               We report the empirical reliability of Gemini models as audio judges that score\n11\t                                               full-duplex agent conversations directly from the raw stereo waveform, tested across\n12\t                                               three models in the Gemini family: 2.5 Flash, 3.5 Flash, and 3.1 Pro. Our pri-\n13\t                                               mary evidence base uses Gemini 2.5 Flash as the ground-truth model, validated\n14\t                                               against three calibrated human raters on 209 stereo sessions, scored on 8 production\n15\tarXiv:2607.07985v1 [cs.CL] 8 Jul 2026\n16\t\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t\n20\t                                               dimensions: 152 full-duplex conversations across 13 accent-and-condition strata, to-\n21\t                                               gether with 57 adversarial defect-injected clips. The evidence for Gemini 2.5 Flash\n22\t                                               is consistent across three tests. (i) On 5 of 8 dimensions the LALM-human Spear-\n23\t                                               man ρ departs from the pairwise human-human ρ by at most 0.07, and on 7 of 8\n24\t                                               dimensions the two quantities’ 95 percent bootstrap confidence intervals overlap.\n25\t                                               (ii) The LALM agrees with the three-rater human mean within 1 point on 60 to\n26\t                                               92 percent of sessions on 6 of 8 dimensions. (iii) On 45 of 48 (defect, dimension)\n27\t                                               cells the LALM is as sensitive as humans or better under Newcombe-Wilson 95\n28\t                                               percent confidence intervals, though most of these are underpowered nulls rather\n29\t                                               than demonstrated parity. Rank-ordering ability transfers across the Gemini fam-\n30\t                                               ily: 3.5 Flash improves simple agreement to 8 of 8 dimensions, while 3.1 Pro rates\n31\t                                               several dimensions markedly lower than humans despite comparable rank correla-\n32\t                                               tion. A model swap should be re-validated on calibration specifically, not assumed\n33\t                                               from rank-correlation alone. We identify four areas where deployment requires care,\n34\t                                               and we estimate that human rating alone for our current evaluation cadence costs\n35\t                                               roughly two orders of magnitude more than the equivalent LALM workload. The\n36\t                                               data presented here provides a defensible empirical basis for deploying the LALM\n37\t                                               as a substitute or fourth rater on the dimensions where the evidence supports it.\n38\t                                               Keywords: LALM-as-judge, audio language models, validation, voice agents, production\n39\t                                               deployment, full-duplex audio.\n40\t\n41\t\n42\t\n43\t                                        1   Background\n44\t                                        Our voice-agent product surface relies on two production audio judges, AgentSpeechFidelity and\n45\t                                        ConversationalAudioQuality, which between them emit ratings on eight dimensions for every eval-\n46\t                                        uated session. To date these judges have been validated informally against single raters on small\n47\t\fsamples. This study addresses a single question: whether LALM-generated ratings agree with\n48\thuman ratings closely enough to substitute for one or more human raters in a production audio-\n49\tevaluation pipeline. We frame substitutability as an empirical, per-dimension property rather than\n50\ta global one, and quantify it against a three-rater human reference standard.\n51\t   Recent work in the LALM-as-judge literature reports strong correlations between LALM judges\n52\tand human Mean Opinion Score (MOS) on isolated text-to-speech utterances [1, 2, 3]. To our\n53\tknowledge, this is the first study to evaluate a LALM as a judge of raw audio from enterprise full-\n54\tduplex agent conversations against a multi-rater human reference standard. We do so over stereo\n55\tagent-client conversations where channel content, turn-taking dynamics, and conversational disflu-\n56\tencies all influence the rating distribution. We extend this line of work to full-duplex conversational\n57\taudio using a production evaluation stack.\n58\t\n59\t\n60\t2   Related Work\n61\tLALM-as-judge for speech. AudioJudge [1] judges speech attributes (pronunciation, rate, quality)\n62\twith high system-level human correlation; ALLD [2] produces descriptive MOS judgements; and\n63\tSpeechQualityLLM [3] predicts dimension-wise MOS. Broad benchmarks such as AIR-Bench [10]\n64\tscore free-form outputs with a text LLM rather than validating an audio judge against humans.\n65\tAll operate on isolated utterances, and none reports multi-rater human validation over full-duplex\n66\tconversational audio.\n67\t    Full-duplex evaluation. Full-Duplex-Bench [8] and its multi-turn successor [9] score turn-taking,\n68\toverlap, and latency of spoken-dialogue systems; the latter judges an automated examiner’s inter-\n69\tactions with an LLM reading transcripts, not the waveform. Both target conversational behaviour\n70\tvia programmatic or transcript-based metrics, not per-dimension audio-fidelity ratings judged from\n71\tthe audio against humans. We fill that gap: we measure how closely a production, audio-native\n72\tLALM judge’s per-dimension ratings track three calibrated humans on stereo full-duplex agent-\n73\tclient conversations.\n74\t   Reliability versus validity. We invoke a long-standing psychometric fact: high raw agreement can\n75\tcoexist with near-zero chance-corrected agreement when ratings saturate near one end of the scale,\n76\tthe ceiling degeneracy of statistics such as Krippendorff α [6]. This is not novel, but it materially\n77\tgoverns how LALM-audio-judge validation should be reported, motivating our per-regime treatment\n78\t(Section 4.2) over a single headline number.\n79\t\n80\t\n81\t3   Study Design\n82\tWe rated 209 sessions in total: 152 full-duplex agent-client conversations spanning 13 accent-\n83\tand-condition strata (six clean strata across the accents American-1, American-2, Indian, British,\n84\tFrench, and Italian, plus seven codec-degraded strata that pair accents with distinct conversational-\n85\tstress personas), together with 57 adversarial perturbed clips derived from held-out high-quality\n86\tbaselines. Sessions were drawn from a production customer-support voice agent. Three Salesforce-\n87\t\n88\t\n89\t\n90\t                                                  2\n91\t\fcontracted annotators, with no prior exposure to the product, scored every session on the eight\n92\tproduction dimensions using a 1-5 Likert scale, with rubric anchors visible at scale points 1, 3, and\n93\t5 and a structured calibration meeting before the main batch began. With 8 dimensions scored by\n94\t3 raters, this yields 209 × 8 × 3 = 5,016 rating observations.\n95\t   We score every session with Gemini 2.5 Flash via the Vertex AI generate-content API, using the\n96\tsame prompts and JSON schemas already in production. Both production judges, AgentSpeechFi-\n97\tdelity (dimensions 1–4) and ConversationalAudioQuality (dimensions 5–8), receive the raw stereo\n98\tWAV audio bytes directly as an audio input part (agent on the left channel, human client on\n99\tthe right), with no transcription or intermediate feature extraction; each returns structured JSON\n100\tscores under the default Vertex AI generation configuration (temperature 1, thinking enabled). We\n101\tcompare the LALM ratings against the three human raters on equal footing, treating the LALM as\n102\ta candidate fourth rater. Adversarial-arm clips are scored by the same judges through an identical\n103\tscoring pipeline. Figure 1 shows the overall design.\n104\t\n105\t                                                     Stereo WAV\n106\t                                                  (agent L / client R)\n107\t\n108\t\n109\t\n110\t\n111\t        2 LALM judges (Gemini 2.5 Flash)                                 3 calibrated human raters\n112\t        raw audio in, default Vertex AI config                            1–5 Likert, anchored rubric\n113\t\n114\t\n115\t\n116\t                                         Per-session × per-dimension\n117\t                                       scores (209 sessions × 8 dimensions)\n118\t\n119\t\n120\t                                                 Agreement analyses\n121\t\n122\t      Figure 1: Study design. Each stereo session is scored independently by two production\n123\t      LALM judges (Gemini 2.5 Flash, raw audio input) and by three calibrated human raters, on\n124\t      the same eight dimensions.\n125\t\n126\t    Across the study we report four agreement statistics, each defined at its point of use and specified\n127\tin full in Appendix D.2 and the surrounding subsections: pairwise Spearman ρ (with 1,000-iteration\n128\tbootstrap 95 percent confidence intervals, seed 42) for rank agreement; the proportion of sessions\n129\twithin 1 point of the three-rater human mean for simple agreement; ordinal Krippendorff α for\n130\tchance-corrected inter-rater reliability; and Newcombe-Wilson hybrid confidence intervals on the\n131\tLALM-minus-human recall difference for the adversarial arm.\n132\t   Figure 2 summarises how the corpus partitions into the analysis pools.\n133\t\n134\t\n135\t\n136\t\n137\t                                                         3\n138\t\f                                  Production customer-support voice agent\n139\t                                       209 rated stereo sessions\n140\t                                        × 8 dimensions × 3 raters\n141\t                                        (5,016 rating observations)\n142\t\n143\t\n144\t             152 conversational sessions                             57 adversarial clips\n145\t             13 accent-and-condition strata                      10 baselines × 6 DSP defects\n146\t              (6 clean + 7 codec-degraded)                      (60 nominal; 3 failed to render)\n147\t\n148\t\n149\t                                                               Recall analysis: 8 baselines with\n150\t                                                                 full 3-rater coverage; n ≤ 8 per\n151\t                                                              (defect, dimension) cell, 4 cells n = 7\n152\t\n153\t      Figure 2: Sample-flow for the 209-session analysis pool. All 209 sessions contribute to the\n154\t      per-dimension agreement statistics (Table 1); the adversarial arm additionally supports the\n155\t      defect-detection analysis, which is restricted to the 8 baselines with complete three-rater\n156\t      coverage.\n157\t\n158\t\n159\t4     Evidence\n160\t4.1    The LALM agrees with humans about as much as humans agree with each other\n161\tWe compute pairwise Spearman ρ between the LALM and each individual human rater, average\n162\tthe three (LALM, human) values, and compare against the average of the three pairwise rater-rater\n163\tSpearman ρ values among the humans (Figure 3). On 5 of 8 dimensions (accent_dialect_handling,\n164\tentity_pronunciation, speech_clarity, prosody_naturalness, and speaking_rate_adaptation), the\n165\tLALM’s agreement with humans is on par with the agreement humans reach among themselves:\n166\tthe LALM-human ρ departs from the human-human ρ by at most 0.07. These are the five tightest-\n167\tmatching dimensions in the corpus (gaps of 0.03 to 0.07), separated by a clear margin from the\n168\tsixth (0.12). On two of them (entity_pronunciation, speech_clarity), the LALM correlates with\n169\thumans more strongly than the humans correlate with each other (0.13 vs 0.09 and 0.08 vs 0.01).\n170\tThis test concerns rank agreement only; a dimension can show near-human rank agreement here yet\n171\tstill have low absolute agreement with the human mean (Section 4.2). speaking_rate_adaptation\n172\tis exactly such a case, and we return to it there.\n173\t   This parity is reinforced by a distributional test. Under 1,000-iteration bootstrap resampling\n174\t(seed 42), the 95 percent confidence interval of the LALM-human ρ overlaps that of the human-\n175\thuman ρ on 7 of 8 dimensions: on those seven, the LALM’s agreement with humans is not statisti-\n176\tcally separable from the agreement humans reach with one another. The exception is audio_clarity,\n177\twhere the intervals are disjoint (human-human [+0.34, +0.58] versus LALM-human [+0.00, +0.30]),\n178\tconsistent with the gap already visible in the point estimates. We read this test as supporting rather\n179\tthan a headline result, since the overlap is driven in part by the wide confidence intervals that the\n180\tmodest inter-human agreement produces; we therefore anchor the comparison on the per-dimension\n181\tgaps above. The human-human interval is not tabulated elsewhere in this paper; it is computed\n182\twith the same bootstrap procedure as Appendix D.4, resampling sessions rather than rater pairs.\n183\t\n184\t\n185\t                                                    4\n186\t\f      Figure 3: Per-dimension Spearman ρ. Blue: pairwise human-human ρ averaged across the\n187\t      three rater pairs. Orange: LALM-human ρ averaged across the three (LALM, human) pairs.\n188\t      Where the two bars are close, the LALM tracks human ratings on par with a fourth human\n189\t      rater on that dimension.\n190\t\n191\t\n192\t   On two further dimensions (audio_clarity, interruption_audio_quality), the LALM correlates\n193\twith humans positively but more weakly than humans correlate with each other. On audio_clarity\n194\tspecifically, human-human ρ is 0.47 and LALM-human ρ is 0.25; the LALM correlation is positive\n195\tbut approximately half the human-human value. On the eighth dimension (overall_fidelity) the\n196\tLALM-human ρ is essentially zero (−0.01), while humans correlate among themselves at only 0.11;\n197\tneither exhibits a strong rank-discrimination signal.\n198\t    The implication for deployment is direct: if the deployment criterion is “does the LALM behave\n199\tlike a fourth human rater?”, the data support yes on 5 of 8 dimensions, partial yes on 2, and\n200\tinconclusive on 1.\n201\t\n202\t4.2   Simple-agreement on production dimensions is high\n203\tFor dimensions where humans saturate at the top of the rating scale, rank correlation can be\n204\tuninformative because the underlying score distribution has very low variance. The complementary\n205\tstatistic is simple agreement: the proportion of sessions where the LALM rating is within 1 point\n206\tof the three-rater human mean. Table 1 reports this number alongside rank correlation and the\n207\tmean human rating.\n208\t    Six of eight dimensions show LALM agreement with the human mean of 60 percent or higher, and\n209\tthree reach 89 percent or above. Two dimensions, speaking_rate_adaptation and overall_fidelity,\n210\tfall below 50 percent. We treat these as the dimensions on which LALM ratings are insufficiently\n211\treliable to serve as a standalone metric (Section 5). Note that speaking_rate_adaptation appeared\n212\tamong the five rank-agreement dimensions in Section 4.1: its LALM-human rank correlation tracks\n213\tthe human-human level, but its absolute LALM-vs-mean within-1 agreement is low, so it is rank-\n214\treliable yet not deployable as a standalone metric. The two criteria measure different things, and\n215\t\n216\t\n217\t                                                 5\n218\t\fDimension                      % within 1      LALM-human ρ          Avg human ρ        Krip. α     Mean human\n219\taccent_dialect_handling               92.3%                 +0.04              +0.08       +0.04            4.88\n220\taudio_clarity                         89.0%                 +0.25              +0.47       +0.03            4.33\n221\tspeech_clarity                        90.9%                 +0.08              +0.01       −0.15            4.43\n222\tentity_pronunciation                  66.5%                 +0.13              +0.09       +0.01            4.71\n223\tprosody_naturalness                   67.5%                 +0.08              +0.11       −0.05            3.94\n224\tinterruption_audio_quality            60.3%                 +0.11              +0.25       +0.05            3.20\n225\tspeaking_rate_adaptation              48.8%                 +0.10              +0.17       +0.08            4.03\n226\toverall_fidelity                      43.5%                 −0.01              +0.11       −0.01            4.38\n227\t\n228\t      Table 1: LALM-vs-human-mean agreement statistics on the full n = 209 3-rater-rated pool\n229\t      (distinct from the adversarial recall analysis in Section 4.3, which is restricted to 8 baselines).\n230\t      “% within 1” is the proportion of sessions where the LALM rating is within 1 point of the\n231\t      across-rater mean human rating; “Avg human ρ” is the average pairwise human-human\n232\t      Spearman ρ; “Krip. α” is the chance-corrected inter-rater Krippendorff α with ordinal\n233\t      weighting [6].\n234\t\n235\t\n236\tspeaking_rate_adaptation is the one dimension where they diverge.\n237\t    The chance-corrected Krippendorff α column exposes why simple agreement is the right lens for\n238\tthese dimensions. Ordinal α is near zero or negative on every dimension, ranging only from −0.15\n239\tto +0.08, even where within-1 agreement exceeds 90 percent, for example α = −0.15 on speech_\n240\tclarity despite 90.9 percent within-1 agreement. This is the reliability paradox in its starkest form:\n241\tthe human panel agrees on the vast majority of sessions in absolute terms, yet a chance-corrected\n242\tstatistic registers essentially no agreement, because the rating variance on a saturated dimension\n243\tis too small for α to resolve. We therefore report α alongside, not instead of, simple agreement,\n244\tand caution that a near-zero α on a ceiling dimension reflects the shape of the rating distribution\n245\trather than genuine rater disagreement.\n246\t\n247\t4.3   Adversarial defect detection: asymmetric sensitivity, few significant cells\n248\tTo test sensitivity to controlled audio degradation, we apply six DSP-level defects (hard ampli-\n249\ttude clipping, dead air, additive Gaussian noise at −2 to −8 dB SNR, mid-utterance truncation,\n250\tphoneme-region overdubbing, and 8 kHz sample-rate down/upsample) to 10 high-baseline-quality\n251\tsessions, a nominal 60-clip corpus of which 57 rendered successfully. We restrict the recall analysis\n252\tto the 8 baselines with full three-rater coverage, giving up to n = 8 per (defect, dimension) cell\n253\t(four cells drop to n = 7). For each cell we measure the recall: the proportion of perturbed clips on\n254\twhich the judge’s score drops by at least 1 point relative to that clip’s baseline. For the LALM the\n255\tscore is its single rating; for humans it is the across-rater mean, so “human recall” is the fraction\n256\tof clips on which the mean human rating dropped by at least 1 point (not a majority- or any-rater\n257\tvote). Newcombe-Wilson hybrid 95 percent confidence intervals on the LALM-minus-human recall\n258\tdifference are reported in Figure 4.\n259\t    On 4 of 48 cells the LALM is significantly more sensitive than humans, on 3 humans are sig-\n260\tnificantly more sensitive, and the remaining 41 show no significant difference (an absence of power\n261\tat n ≤ 8, not demonstrated equivalence). These flags come from Newcombe-Wilson intervals that\n262\t\n263\t\n264\t                                                      6\n265\t\f      Figure 4: Forest plot of LALM-minus-human recall difference across all 48 (defect,\n266\t      dimension) cells. Orange: 4 cells where the LALM is significantly more sensitive than humans\n267\t      (CI excludes 0 above). Blue: 3 cells where humans are significantly more sensitive. Gray: 41\n268\t      cells with no significant difference.\n269\t\n270\t\n271\ttreat the two recalls as independent; because both judges score the same clips, a paired McNemar\n272\tre-test is stricter, and under it only the two most extreme cells remain significant (Appendix D.3).\n273\tOf the 3 cells where the LALM misses artefacts humans catch, two fall on audio_clarity (clipping\n274\tand sample-rate mismatch), and the third is signal-to-noise degradation on entity_pronunciation.\n275\tThe two audio_clarity misses are the operationally salient pair, since despite coming from two\n276\tdifferent DSP mechanisms (amplitude clipping and sample-rate aliasing), they concentrate on the\n277\tsame dimension. The implication for deployment is that for the broad defect-detection use case,\n278\tswapping in the LALM does not meaningfully reduce coverage; for the narrow audio_clarity blind\n279\tspot, an additional check is warranted (Section 5).\n280\t   The most instructive pattern is that the LALM’s response to a single artefact is dimension-\n281\tdependent. Hard amplitude clipping is a clear example: under clipping the LALM lowers prosody_\n282\t\n283\t                                                   7\n284\t\fnaturalness and overall_fidelity on 4 of 8 clips (where humans lower neither, 0 of 8), yet lowers\n285\taudio_clarity on 0 of 8 (where humans lower it on all 8). The identical waveform corruption is thus\n286\tregistered by the LALM as a prosody and fidelity problem but not as a clarity problem, while human\n287\traters do the reverse. We read this as evidence that the two judges route the same acoustic evidence\n288\tto different rubric constructs: the LALM appears to treat clipping-induced spectral distortion\n289\tas unnatural delivery (prosody, overall fidelity), whereas humans categorise the same distortion\n290\tas degraded signal quality (audio_clarity). The pattern recurs for other artefacts, sample-rate\n291\tmismatch is caught by humans on audio_clarity (0.71 recall) but not the LALM (0.00), while signal-\n292\tto-noise degradation is caught by the LALM on accent handling, where humans miss it entirely\n293\t(0.00 recall); on interruption quality the same defect is caught by both judges, though the LALM\n294\tcatches more (1.00 vs. 0.625). The operational consequence is that LALM and human coverage\n295\tare complementary rather than nested: a session flagged by neither is more trustworthy than one\n296\tflagged by either alone, which argues for retaining a human spot-check tier on the specific (artefact,\n297\tdimension) pairs where the LALM is blind, rather than for a uniform confidence adjustment.\n298\t\n299\t4.4   The LALM is architecturally more consistent than human raters\n300\tA deployment-relevant property of an LLM judge is intra-judge consistency. Both judges ran under\n301\tthe default Vertex AI generation configuration (temperature 1, thinking enabled) for this study, so\n302\twe make no determinism claim from configuration alone; even a temperature-0 setting would not\n303\tguarantee exactly reproducible output run to run [11]. The more robust argument is architectural:\n304\tan automated judge has no analogue to a human rater’s fatigue, mood, or drifting rubric interpreta-\n305\ttion over a multi-week batch, so it is structurally more consistent than a human panel independent\n306\tof the exact sampling configuration. Human raters offer no such guarantee. Between-rater variation\n307\tin our pool is substantial: rater means on the same dimension differ by more than a full point on\n308\tsome dimensions, by 1.11 points on speech_clarity (3.74 vs 4.85) and 1.12 points on audio_clarity\n309\t(3.66 vs 4.78). We stress that this is a stability property, not an accuracy property: this observation\n310\tspeaks to reproducibility of the headline metric rather than to correctness, which the preceding\n311\tagreement tests address. A related observation is that LALM-vs-human-mean agreement (Table 1)\n312\tis in many cases as high as the agreement between any individual human-rater pair, because the\n313\tLALM tends toward the central tendency the human panel collectively expresses. For production\n314\tmonitoring, where a stable and reproducible headline number is valuable in its own right, this is a\n315\tuseful operating point.\n316\t\n317\t4.5   Decomposition: agreement on natural conversations alone\n318\tThe agreement pool in Table 1 combines 152 natural full-duplex conversations with the 57 ad-\n319\tversarial perturbed clips. Table 2 recomputes the same statistics on the 152 natural conversations\n320\talone, the population a deployed judge actually scores, and the headline results hold: the LALM-\n321\thuman ρ still lands within 0.07 of the human-human ρ on 5 of 8 dimensions, and within-1 agreement\n322\tstill exceeds 60 percent on 6 of 8. Neither top-line claim depends on the adversarial clips. One\n323\tdimension, however, shifts substantially, and the shift is itself informative. On the pooled data,\n324\t\n325\t\n326\t                                                  8\n327\t\faudio_clarity looked like an informative dimension where humans rank-agree strongly (human-\n328\thuman ρ = 0.47) and the LALM trails (0.25); on natural conversations alone, the human-human\n329\tρ falls to 0.07 and the LALM-human ρ to 0.04. The pooled correlation was therefore measuring\n330\tshared sensitivity to the injected defects, not rank agreement on natural audio, on which humans\n331\tthemselves barely rank-discriminate. Restricted to natural conversations, no dimension exhibits\n332\tstrong human rank-discrimination (the highest human-human ρ is 0.27, on interruption_audio_\n333\tquality); the LALM is a defensible fourth rater precisely in the near-ceiling regime that dominates\n334\treal traffic, and there is correspondingly no strong-rank-discrimination dimension for it to fall short\n335\ton.\n336\t\n337\tDimension                     % within 1     LALM-human ρ         Avg human ρ       Krip. α    Mean human\n338\taccent_dialect_handling             94.1%                 +0.07             +0.08      +0.05           4.86\n339\taudio_clarity                       92.8%                 +0.04             +0.07      −0.29           4.59\n340\tspeech_clarity                      92.8%                 +0.02             +0.01      −0.13           4.47\n341\tentity_pronunciation                63.8%                 +0.12             +0.12      +0.07           4.73\n342\tprosody_naturalness                 69.7%                 +0.06             +0.14      +0.02           3.92\n343\tinterruption_audio_quality          60.5%                 +0.12             +0.27      +0.05           3.05\n344\tspeaking_rate_adaptation            59.9%                 +0.10             +0.11      +0.03           3.88\n345\toverall_fidelity                    40.8%                 −0.06             +0.20      +0.12           4.39\n346\t\n347\t      Table 2: Agreement statistics on the 152 natural conversations only (the adversarial arm\n348\t      excluded), directly comparable to Table 1. The two headline counts (5 of 8 within 0.07; 6 of 8\n349\t      above 60 percent within-1) are unchanged; audio_clarity’s human-human ρ falls from 0.47 to\n350\t      0.07 once the engineered variation of the adversarial clips is removed.\n351\t\n352\t\n353\t4.6   Cross-model replication\n354\tEvery result so far uses a single model, Gemini 2.5 Flash. To check whether the agreement pattern\n355\tis a property of the approach or an artefact of that one model, we re-scored all 209 sessions with the\n356\tsame two judges, changing nothing but the underlying LALM, against two further Gemini models\n357\tfrom a newer model family: Gemini 3.5 Flash and Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview. Both re-scoring runs\n358\tcompleted with zero errors across all 418 (session, judge) calls.\n359\t   Gemini 3.5 Flash reproduces the paper’s central finding, with a mixed comparison to Gemini\n360\t2.5 Flash: within-1 agreement with the human mean improves to 8 of 8 dimensions (versus 6\n361\tof 8), while the rank-correlation gap stays within 0.07 of the human-human baseline on 4 of 8\n362\tdimensions, one fewer than Gemini 2.5 Flash’s 5 of 8, with the remaining four at 0.08–0.15 except\n363\taudio_clarity, which trails on every model tested (Appendix B.2). The result we would most want\n364\ta second model to confirm, that the LALM is a defensible fourth rater on most dimensions, holds\n365\tagain on an independently trained, later-generation model, which is the strongest evidence in this\n366\tpaper that the finding is about the approach rather than about one checkpoint.\n367\t   Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview tells a more qualified story: its rank correlations are comparable to the\n368\tother two models, but its absolute scores run substantially below the human mean on several dimen-\n369\tsions, most severely audio_clarity (−1.52 points) and speaking_rate_adaptation (−1.44 points),\n370\twhich pulls its within-1 agreement below 60 percent on three dimensions. This is a calibration\n371\t\n372\t                                                    9\n373\t\foffset rather than a ranking failure, and we return to its deployment implication in Section 5.4.\n374\t\n375\t                Model                     Rank-corr. within 0.07       Within-1 ≥60%\n376\t                gemini-2.5-flash                              5 of 8              6 of 8\n377\t                gemini-3.5-flash                              4 of 8              8 of 8\n378\t                gemini-3.1-pro-preview                        5 of 8              5 of 8\n379\t\n380\t      Table 3: Headline agreement counts across all three models tested. Rank-correlation transfers\n381\t      consistently (4–5 of 8 dimensions within the 0.07 gap threshold for every model); simple\n382\t      agreement is where gemini-3.1-pro-preview diverges, driven by the calibration offset detailed\n383\t      above rather than a ranking failure. Full per-dimension results in Appendix B.2.\n384\t\n385\t\n386\t\n387\t5     Where Deployment Requires Care\n388\tFour areas of the result space ask for additional handling before deployment is recommended without\n389\tqualification.\n390\t\n391\t5.1    audio_clarity rank-discrimination gap\n392\tThe rank-discrimination gap on audio_clarity identified in Section 4.1 lives almost entirely in the\n393\tdegraded-audio regime supplied by the adversarial clips (Section 4.5): on natural conversations both\n394\tcorrelations are near zero. That makes the gap operationally relevant exactly where it matters,\n395\twhen audio quality is actually compromised. The LALM is still positively correlated and agrees on\n396\t89 percent of sessions within 1 point, so the deployment risk is not that LALM ratings are wrong\n397\ton average, but that they are less reliable on the relative ranking of two sessions of comparable but\n398\timperfect audio. Routing audio_clarity into a human-pair sample for any session where the LALM\n399\trating is below 4 would resolve this without losing the cost benefit on the 89 percent of sessions\n400\twhere the LALM agrees with humans cleanly.\n401\t\n402\t5.2    Clipping artefacts on audio_clarity specifically\n403\tOn the cell clip × audio_clarity, humans unanimously detect the artefact (8 of 8) and the LALM\n404\tunanimously fails to (0 of 8). This is a directional miss large enough to matter if audio_clarity\n405\tis judged exclusively by the LALM and amplitude clipping is a known production artefact. A\n406\tlightweight DSP detector for hard amplitude clipping (which is cheap to compute on the raw audio\n407\tbuffer) could route any session where clipping is detected into a human review queue, leaving the\n408\tLALM as the headline judge on the remaining sessions. This is one of only two cells in the entire\n409\t48-cell study robust to the paired McNemar re-test (Appendix D.3); the other is signal-to-noise\n410\tdegradation on entity_pronunciation (Section 4.3), which warrants an analogous safeguard for that\n411\tdimension. A second audio_clarity miss, sample-rate mismatch, is directional (0 of 7 LALM vs. 5\n412\tof 7 human) but does not survive the paired test.\n413\t\n414\t\n415\t\n416\t\n417\t                                                   10\n418\t\f5.3    Two contentious dimensions need rubric work, not LALM work\n419\tOn overall_fidelity and speaking_rate_adaptation, neither humans nor the LALM produce reliable\n420\trank-correlation signals: human-human ρ is 0.11 and 0.17, LALM-human ρ is −0.01 and 0.10. These\n421\tdimensions are not saturated at the top of the scale the way accent_dialect_handling is (median\n422\trating 4.33 and 4.00 respectively, versus a median of 5.00 there), despite mean ratings of 4.38 and\n423\t4.03; humans simply disagree about what the rubrics mean. The blocker on these dimensions is\n424\trubric construct validity, not the LALM. We recommend dropping them from headline deployment\n425\tmetrics while a rubric reformulation pass is underway, and then re-running this validation post-\n426\trevision to test whether anchor sharpening drives them into the cleanly-deployable regime.\n427\t\n428\t5.4    Re-check calibration, not just ranking, after a model swap\n429\tSection 4.6 found that rank-ordering ability transferred cleanly across two further Gemini models,\n430\tbut absolute calibration did not: Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview rates audio_clarity and speaking_rate_\n431\tadaptation more than a full Likert point below the human mean on average, which alone drops\n432\tthose two dimensions’ within-1 agreement to 34.9 percent and 37.3 percent respectively (Appendix\n433\tTable 7), well below the 60 percent bar this paper otherwise treats as a usability floor. A team that\n434\tswaps the underlying model expecting the validation to carry over should not assume it does: rank-\n435\tcorrelation checks alone would have missed this, since Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview’s rank correlation\n436\tgap is within 0.07 of the human-human baseline on 5 of 8 dimensions, including speaking_rate_\n437\tadaptation, one of the two dimensions where its calibration is furthest off, and matches Gemini 2.5\n438\tFlash while exceeding Gemini 3.5 Flash on this measure (Table 3). We recommend re-running the\n439\tsimple-agreement check in Section 4.2 specifically, on a small session sample, before promoting any\n440\tmodel swap to production, rather than relying on rank-correlation parity as a proxy for calibration\n441\tparity.\n442\t\n443\t\n444\t6     Cost and Operational Implications\n445\tThis is a directional internal estimate, not a reproducible unit-cost model. Under conservative\n446\thuman-side assumptions, a calibrated rater needs 6 to 8 minutes to score a 5-minute session across\n447\tall eight dimensions, so three-rater coverage of a 100-session weekly batch is roughly 35 person-\n448\thours, about 0.88 of a fully-loaded engineering FTE. The LALM alternative is two API calls per\n449\tsession (one per judge), a few dollars per week dominated by audio input tokens. We do not claim\n450\ta precise ratio, but the gap between roughly one FTE of rater time and a few-dollar API bill is of\n451\torder two magnitudes, even after reserving full human review for the two contentious dimensions\n452\tand a 10 percent spot-check on the rest.\n453\t   The throughput unlock matters more than the dollar saving. Three-rater human coverage caps\n454\thow many sessions we can audit per week; with the LALM as primary judge and humans as a\n455\tspot-check and escalation tier, that cap shifts from rater hours to engineering attention, making a\n456\t1,000-session weekly cadence feasible without added rater capacity.\n457\t\n458\t\n459\t\n460\t\n461\t                                                 11\n462\t\f7   Limitations of This Evidence\n463\tFive caveats deserve naming explicitly. First, the primary evidence base is a single LALM (Gemini\n464\t2.5 Flash) on a single production customer-support agent; generalisation to other agents would\n465\tstill warrant a fresh validation. We partially address model generalisation directly (Section 4.6):\n466\trank-ordering ability replicated on two further Gemini models, but calibration did not on one of\n467\tthem (Section 5.4), so a model swap should be treated as requiring its own simple-agreement check,\n468\tnot assumed to inherit this validation’s headline numbers. Second, our human reference standard\n469\trests on only three raters; a larger panel would tighten the human-human agreement estimates and\n470\tbetter generalise our conclusions; a larger-rater-pool remains the cleanest validity test. Third, the\n471\tadversarial arm’s n = 7–8 per (defect, dimension) cell is too small for Newcombe-Wilson CIs to\n472\tresolve close cells; the 41 non-significant cells reflect a lack of power, not demonstrated equivalence,\n473\tso the “matches” half of the 45-of-48 figure means “no detectable difference at this sample size,”\n474\tnot proven parity. Fourth, the 48-cell adversarial analysis has no multiple-comparisons correction;\n475\troughly 2 to 3 of the 7 flagged cells could be false positives at 95 percent, so we treat them as\n476\thypotheses to confirm, not established effects, relying on the aggregate pattern rather than any\n477\tsingle cell. Fifth, LALM and human recall are paired, not independent as Newcombe-Wilson\n478\tassumes; an exact paired McNemar re-test (Appendix D.3) confirms only the two most extreme\n479\tcells of seven. None of these caveats change the recommendation that the evidence supports phased\n480\tdeployment with the safeguards in Section 5.\n481\t\n482\t\n483\t8   Conclusion\n484\tOn a 209-session corpus (152 full-duplex agent conversations across 13 strata and 57 adversarial\n485\tdefect-injected clips), Gemini 2.5 Flash matches the rank-correlation level of the human-rater pool\n486\ton five of eight dimensions, agrees with the across-rater human mean within 1 point on 60 to 92\n487\tpercent of sessions on six of eight dimensions, and in the adversarial arm is significantly more\n488\tdefect-sensitive than humans on 4 of 48 (defect, dimension) cells and less sensitive on 3, with no\n489\tdetectable difference on the remaining 41 at this sample size. These are the standard agreement\n490\tstatistics that LALM-as-judge validation studies are scored on, and on each of them the evidence\n491\tsupports deploying the LALM as a substitute or fourth rater, provided the safeguards in Section 5\n492\tare in place. A cross-model check (Section 4.6) found that this pattern is not an artefact of the\n493\tspecific model: rank-ordering ability held on two further Gemini models, though one of them\n494\trequired a calibration correction that rank-correlation alone would not have surfaced (Section 5.4),\n495\twhich we take as a reason to verify calibration explicitly after any future model swap rather than as\n496\ta reason to doubt the underlying approach. The approximate two-orders-of-magnitude operational\n497\tcost reduction and the throughput unlock that follow are downstream consequences of this validity\n498\tclaim, not arguments for it.\n499\t\n500\t\n501\t\n502\t\n503\t                                                  12\n504\t\fReferences\n505\t[1] P. Manakul, W. H. Gan, M. J. Ryan, A. S. Khan, W. Sirichotedumrong, K. Pipatanakul,\n506\t     W. Held, and D. Yang, “AudioJudge: Understanding what works in large audio model based\n507\t     speech evaluation,” arXiv:2507.12705, 2025.\n508\t[2] C. Chen, Y. Hu, S. Wang, H. Wang, Z. Chen, C. Zhang, C.-H. H. Yang, and E. S. Chng,\n509\t     “Audio large language models can be descriptive speech quality evaluators,” in Proc. ICLR,\n510\t     2025. arXiv:2501.17202.\n511\t[3] M. Monjur and S. Nirjon, “SpeechQualityLLM: LLM-based multimodal assessment of speech\n512\t     quality,” arXiv:2512.08238, 2025.\n513\t[4] R. G. Newcombe, “Interval estimation for the difference between independent proportions:\n514\t     comparison of eleven methods,” Statistics in Medicine, vol. 17, no. 8, pp. 873–890, 1998.\n515\t[5] International Telecommunication Union, “ITU-T Recommendation P.808: Subjective evalua-\n516\t     tion of speech quality with a crowdsourcing approach,” Geneva, Switzerland, 2021.\n517\t[6] K. Krippendorff, Content Analysis: An Introduction to its Methodology, 4th ed., Thousand\n518\t     Oaks, CA: SAGE Publications, 2018.\n519\t[7] Salesforce Applied AI Research, eVerse team, “LALM Judge Validation on Full-Duplex Voice\n520\t     Agents,” Hugging Face Dataset, 2026. [Online]. Available: https://huggingface.co/\n521\t     datasets/armaan-sayyad/lalm-judge-validation-full-duplex\n522\t[8] G.-T. Lin, J. Lian, T. Li, Q. Wang, G. Anumanchipalli, A. H. Liu, and H.-y. Lee, “Full-\n523\t     Duplex-Bench: A benchmark to evaluate full-duplex spoken dialogue models on turn-taking\n524\t     capabilities,” arXiv:2503.04721, 2025.\n525\t[9] G.-T. Lin, S.-Y. S. Kuan, J. Shi, K.-W. Chang, S. Arora, S. Watanabe, and H.-y. Lee, “Full-\n526\t     Duplex-Bench v2: A multi-turn evaluation framework for duplex dialogue systems with an\n527\t     automated examiner,” arXiv:2510.07838, 2025.\n528\t[10] Q. Yang, J. Xu, W. Liu, Y. Chu, Z. Jiang, X. Zhou, Y. Leng, Y. Lv, Z. Zhao, C. Zhou, and\n529\t     J. Zhou, “AIR-Bench: Benchmarking large audio-language models via generative comprehen-\n530\t     sion,” in Proc. ACL, 2024. arXiv:2402.07729.\n531\t[11] B. Atil, S. Aykent, A. Chittams, L. Fu, R. J. Passonneau, E. Radcliffe, G. R. Rajagopal, A.\n532\t     Sloan, T. Tudrej, F. Ture, Z. Wu, L. Xu, and B. Baldwin, “Non-determinism of ‘deterministic’\n533\t     LLM settings,” arXiv:2408.04667, 2024.\n534\t\n535\t\n536\t\n537\t\n538\t                                               13\n539\t\fAppendix\n540\tA     Study Design Details\n541\tA.1    Full 14-stratum breakdown\n542\tTable 4 lists every stratum in the analysis pool, with its sample size, accent, persona, codec setting,\n543\tand background-noise setting. The 14 rows comprise 13 conversational strata (152 sessions) and\n544\tthe adversarial arm (57 perturbed clips), summing to the full 209-session pool. The Italian clean\n545\tcondition contributes a partial five-session batch (baseline-italian-5); it is retained in the pool\n546\tbut is smaller than the other clean strata because collection was cut short.\n547\t\n548\t             Config               Accent        Persona               Codec      Noise    n\n549\t             clean-american-1     American-1    neutral                  off      off     10\n550\t             clean-american-2     American-2    neutral                  off      off     38\n551\t             clean-indian         Indian        neutral                  off      off     10\n552\t             clean-british        British       neutral                  off      off     10\n553\t             clean-french         French        neutral                  off      off     10\n554\t             baseline-italian-5   Italian       neutral                  off      off      5\n555\t             codec-american-1     American-1    barge-in                 on       off      9\n556\t             codec-american-2     American-2    dual-conversation        on       off     10\n557\t             codec-indian         Indian        slow-speech              on       off     10\n558\t             codec-indian-2       Indian        rapid-speech             on       off     10\n559\t             codec-british        British       whisper                  on       off     10\n560\t             codec-french         French        fragmented-speech        on       off     10\n561\t             codec-italian        Italian       steamroll                on       off     10\n562\t             adversarial          American-1    neutral (perturbed)   baseline   DSP      57\n563\t\n564\t      Table 4: Full stratum breakdown of the 209-session analysis pool (152 conversational\n565\t      sessions across 13 strata plus 57 adversarial perturbed clips). Persona identifies the\n566\t      simulated-client behavioural mode used for that cell.\n567\t\n568\t\n569\t    The adversarial arm applies six perturbations to each of 10 high-baseline-quality sessions, a\n570\tnominal 60-clip corpus; 57 clips rendered successfully (3 perturbations failed to generate), which\n571\tis the count shown for the adversarial row in Table 4. The recall analysis is restricted to the 8\n572\tbaselines with full three-rater coverage on both the baseline and its perturbed siblings, yielding up\n573\tto n = 8 per (defect, dimension) cell. Four cells drop to n = 7: recall requires a LALM baseline\n574\tscore, a LALM perturbed score, and the human rating for the same (defect, dimension), and in\n575\tthese four cells one of those components is missing for a single clip (the clip itself rendered and was\n576\trated on the other dimensions), so that clip is excluded from the affected cell only.\n577\t\n578\tA.2    Rater calibration protocol\n579\tThree Salesforce-contracted annotators, with no prior exposure to the product, served on the panel\n580\tand are referred to as R1, R2, R3 throughout the paper and this appendix. Calibration followed a\n581\ttwo-stage protocol:\n582\t\n583\t• Round 1 (individual): each rater independently scored the same 5-session calibration set on all 8\n584\t\n585\t                                                   14\n586\t\f   dimensions using the rubric anchors listed in Appendix A.3, without seeing each other’s ratings.\n587\t• Meeting: the three raters and a moderator reviewed disagreements dimension by dimension,\n588\t  discussed cases where the rubric was ambiguous, and agreed on interpretation. No rubric anchors\n589\t  were changed post-meeting; interpretation notes were captured informally.\n590\t• Round 2 (main batch): raters scored the full 209-session analysis pool, which comprises the\n591\t  152 conversational sessions and the 57 adversarial perturbed clips, using the aligned rubric\n592\t  interpretation. Rating order was randomised across raters to avoid correlated fatigue effects.\n593\t\n594\t   Raters scored sessions through an internal eVerse annotation tool (built for this evaluation\n595\tworkflow, distinct from the Labelforce labeling product). Raters were blind to which sessions were\n596\tnatural conversations versus adversarial perturbed clips, and were never shown the LALM’s scores\n597\tat any point before or during their own rating.\n598\t\n599\tA.3    Rubric anchors\n600\tThe rubrics below are abbreviated for space, showing the anchor descriptions at scale points 1, 3,\n601\tand 5; the full rubric text (all five points, with entity-type lists and worked examples) is embedded\n602\tin the LALM prompt reproduced in Appendix A.4 and released in the supplementary archive.\n603\tRaters may use 2 and 4 as intermediate values. Rating on a 5-point Likert scale with anchor\n604\tdescriptions follows the general protocol of ITU-T Recommendation P.808 [5], adapted here for\n605\tfull-duplex two-channel conversation audio.\n606\t\n607\t\n608\tentity_pronunciation\n609\t\n610\t• 5 (Perfect): All entities pronounced clearly, correctly, and distinctly.\n611\t• 3 (Acceptable): 2–3 minor issues or one moderate issue (e.g. wrong digit, unclear letter).\n612\t• 1 (Very Poor): Critical entities are incomprehensible or majorly incorrect.\n613\t\n614\t\n615\tspeech_clarity\n616\t\n617\t• 5: Every word is perfectly clear and easy to understand.\n618\t• 3: Some words unclear but overall understandable.\n619\t• 1: Speech is often incomprehensible or heavily distorted.\n620\t\n621\t\n622\tprosody_naturalness\n623\t\n624\t• 5 (Indistinguishable from human): Natural pitch, rhythm, stress, and emotional expres-\n625\t  siveness.\n626\t• 3 (Acceptable): Recognisably synthetic but acceptable; somewhat robotic.\n627\t• 1 (Very robotic): Monotone, mechanical, uncanny-valley.\n628\t\n629\t                                                 15\n630\t\foverall_fidelity The production LALM judge emits this dimension on a 0–2 scale, which we\n631\trescale to 1–5 (0→1, 1→3, 2→5) for comparison with the other seven dimensions; the LALM\n632\ttherefore occupies only the three values {1, 3, 5} on this dimension. Human raters, by contrast, use\n633\tthe full 1–5 scale. The overall_fidelity agreement figures thus compare a coarse three-point LALM\n634\tgrid against five-point human ratings, and should be read with that granularity mismatch in mind;\n635\tit is one reason we classify overall_fidelity as a contentious dimension on which LALM ratings are\n636\tnot deployable as a standalone metric.\n637\t\n638\t• 2 (High): All critical entities correct, clear speech, natural prosody, no major quality issues.\n639\t• 1 (Medium): Most entities correct; clear speech with minor artefacts; prosody acceptable.\n640\t• 0 (Low): Critical entity errors, clarity issues that impair comprehension, or very robotic\n641\t  prosody.\n642\t\n643\t\n644\tinterruption_audio_quality\n645\t\n646\t• 5: Seamless overlaps, no pops/clicks/clipping.\n647\t• 3: Minor audio artefacts at transitions but understandable.\n648\t• 1: Severe audio corruption during interruptions.\n649\t\n650\t\n651\tspeaking_rate_adaptation\n652\t\n653\t• 5: Agent perfectly matches caller’s pace.\n654\t• 3: Fixed agent pace that is acceptable but does not adapt.\n655\t• 1: Major pace mismatch that makes conversation awkward.\n656\t\n657\t\n658\taccent_dialect_handling\n659\t\n660\t• 5: Conversation flows naturally regardless of accent; appropriate style match.\n661\t• 3: Acceptable conversation despite accent differences.\n662\t• 1: Accent mismatch causes confusion.\n663\t\n664\t\n665\taudio_clarity\n666\t\n667\t• 5: Crystal clear audio, natural silences, consistent volume.\n668\t• 3: Acceptable quality with minor background noise or volume issues.\n669\t• 1: Poor audio quality, excessive noise, inconsistent volume, dead air.\n670\t\n671\t\n672\t\n673\t\n674\t                                                16\n675\t\fA.4    LALM prompts and JSON schemas\n676\tTwo prompts are used, matching the two production judges: AgentSpeechFidelity (dimensions\n677\t1–4) and ConversationalAudioQuality (dimensions 5–8). Both are shown to Gemini 2.5 Flash\n678\twith the stereo WAV attached as an audio part. This section reproduces the JSON output schemas\n679\tverbatim and paraphrases the prompt structure; the full, unedited prompt text for both judges\n680\tis released in the supplementary archive as speech_fidelity_prompt.py and conversational_\n681\taudio_quality.py.\n682\t\n683\t\n684\tCommon preamble (paraphrased from both prompts) Both judges are told the WAV is a\n685\tstereo full-duplex recording with the AI agent on the LEFT channel and the human caller on the\n686\tRIGHT channel. The judges are asked to focus on the AGENT channel for AgentSpeechFidelity\n687\tand on the two-party interaction for ConversationalAudioQuality. Both return structured JSON\n688\tmatching the schemas below.\n689\t\n690\t\n691\tAgentSpeechFidelity output schema (verbatim)\n692\t\n693\t{\n694\t    \"entity_pronunciation\": {\n695\t      \"score\": <int 1-5>,\n696\t      \"entities_evaluated\": [\n697\t         {\"text\": <str>, \"type\": <str>,\n698\t          \"correct\": <bool>, \"notes\": <str>}\n699\t      ],\n700\t      \"issues\": [<str>],\n701\t      \"justification\": <str>\n702\t    },\n703\t    \"speech_clarity\": {\n704\t      \"score\": <int 1-5>,\n705\t      \"justification\": <str>\n706\t    },\n707\t    \"prosody_naturalness\": {\n708\t      \"score\": <int 1-5>,\n709\t      \"justification\": <str>\n710\t    },\n711\t    \"overall_fidelity\": {\n712\t      \"rating\": <int 0-2>,\n713\t      \"reasoning\": <str>\n714\t    }\n715\t}\n716\t\n717\t\n718\t\n719\t                                             17\n720\t\fConversationalAudioQuality output schema (verbatim, with the intended range noted)\n721\tUnlike AgentSpeechFidelity, the ConversationalAudioQuality JSON schema constrains score\n722\tto type integer only; it does not enforce a minimum or maximum in the schema itself. The 1–5\n723\trange is required by the prompt and rubric, not by schema validation.\n724\t\n725\t{\n726\t    \"interruption_audio_quality\":\n727\t      {\"score\": <int>, \"justification\": <str>},\n728\t    \"speaking_rate_adaptation\":\n729\t      {\"score\": <int>, \"justification\": <str>},\n730\t    \"accent_dialect_handling\":\n731\t      {\"score\": <int>, \"justification\": <str>},\n732\t    \"audio_clarity\":\n733\t      {\"score\": <int>, \"justification\": <str>}\n734\t}\n735\t\n736\tPrompt/rubric-intended range: 1–5 for all four dimensions.\n737\t    Both prompts embed the same rubric anchors listed in Appendix A.3. The full prompt source\n738\tfiles are included in the reproducibility manifest (Appendix E).\n739\t\n740\t\n741\tB     Full Numerical Results\n742\tB.1    Complete per-dimension agreement statistics\n743\tTable 5 reports every agreement statistic used in the paper on the full 209-session pool. Bootstrap\n744\t95% CIs on LALM-human ρ use 1,000 iterations with session resampling. Source: h1_per_dim.csv\n745\tand lalm_as_4th_rater.csv.\n746\t\n747\t             Dimension                    ρHH      ρLH               CI    %≤1     L%1 Mean H\n748\t             audio_clarity                +0.47   +0.25   [+0.00, +0.30]   67.0%   89.0%   4.33\n749\t             interruption_audio_quality   +0.25   +0.11   [+0.03, +0.29]   17.7%   60.3%   3.20\n750\t             speaking_rate_adaptation     +0.17   +0.10   [+0.02, +0.26]   54.5%   48.8%   4.03\n751\t             accent_dialect_handling      +0.08   +0.04   [−0.12, +0.17]   88.5%   92.3%   4.88\n752\t             entity_pronunciation         +0.09   +0.13   [+0.04, +0.32]   76.6%   66.5%   4.71\n753\t             speech_clarity               +0.01   +0.08   [+0.04, +0.33]   50.7%   90.9%   4.43\n754\t             overall_fidelity             +0.11   −0.01   [−0.13, +0.15]   62.2%   43.5%   4.38\n755\t             prosody_naturalness          +0.11   +0.08   [+0.03, +0.28]   52.2%   67.5%   3.94\n756\t\n757\t       Table 5: Per-dimension agreement on n = 209 sessions. ρHH is the average pairwise\n758\t       human-human Spearman ρ; ρLH is the average LALM-human ρ across the three (LALM,\n759\t       rater) pairs; CI is the bootstrap 95% CI on ρLH ; %≤1 is the three-rater max-min spread ≤ 1;\n760\t       L%1 is the LALM-vs-human-mean within-1 proportion.\n761\t\n762\t\n763\tB.2    Cross-model replication: gemini-3.5-flash and gemini-3.1-pro-preview\n764\tTo check whether the agreement pattern in Table 5 is specific to Gemini 2.5 Flash or holds across\n765\tmodel choice, we re-scored all 209 sessions with both judges (AgentSpeechFidelity, Conversation-\n766\t\n767\t                                                     18\n768\t\falAudioQuality) unchanged, swapping only the underlying model. Two further Gemini models\n769\tfrom a newer model family were available to us at the time of writing: gemini-3.5-flash and\n770\tgemini-3.1-pro-preview. Both were called via the Vertex AI generateContent API at each\n771\tmodel’s default sampling configuration. All 209 sessions × 2 judges = 418 calls per model com-\n772\tpleted with zero errors for both models.\n773\t   Table 6 reports Gemini 3.5 Flash’s full per-dimension results, directly comparable to Table 5.\n774\tSimple agreement improves on the original: 8 of 8 dimensions exceed 60% within-1 agreement\n775\t(versus 6 of 8 for Gemini 2.5 Flash). The rank-correlation gap is within 0.07 on 4 of 8 dimensions,\n776\tone fewer than Gemini 2.5 Flash’s 5 of 8, though the gaps on the dimensions that miss the threshold\n777\tare still modest (0.08–0.15 on all but audio_clarity). audio_clarity remains the one dimension\n778\twhere the LALM-human ρ trails the human-human ρ by a wide margin (0.26), consistent with\n779\tSection 4.5’s finding that this gap is a property of the adversarial-arm audio regime, not of any one\n780\tmodel.\n781\t\n782\t            Dimension                    ρHH      ρLH    Gap     L%1 Mean L Mean H     Bias\n783\t            accent_dialect_handling      +0.08   +0.12    0.04   95.7%   4.53   4.88   −0.35\n784\t            audio_clarity                +0.47   +0.21    0.26   82.3%   4.14   4.33   −0.20\n785\t            speech_clarity               +0.01   +0.09    0.08   94.3%   4.74   4.43   +0.30\n786\t            entity_pronunciation         +0.09   +0.18    0.09   81.8%   4.57   4.71   −0.14\n787\t            prosody_naturalness          +0.11   +0.13    0.02   92.3%   3.86   3.94   −0.08\n788\t            interruption_audio_quality   +0.25   +0.40    0.15   70.3%   3.74   3.20   +0.55\n789\t            speaking_rate_adaptation     +0.17   +0.20    0.04   69.4%   3.28   4.03   −0.75\n790\t            overall_fidelity             +0.11   +0.14    0.03   74.2%   4.36   4.38   −0.02\n791\t\n792\t      Table 6: Per-dimension agreement for gemini-3.5-flash on the same n = 209 session pool,\n793\t      directly comparable to Table 5. ρHH is unchanged from Table 5 (same human raters, same\n794\t      sessions); Gap is |ρLH − ρHH |; L%1 is the LALM-vs-human-mean within-1 proportion;\n795\t      Bias is the mean LALM score minus the mean human score (negative: LALM rates lower\n796\t      than humans on average). Source: h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv.\n797\t\n798\t\n799\t   Table 7 reports the same statistics for Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview. Rank correlation is comparable\n800\tto the other two models (5 of 8 dimensions within the 0.07 gap threshold), but simple agree-\n801\tment is weaker on several dimensions because the model’s mean score runs substantially below\n802\tthe human mean: by −1.52 points on audio_clarity, −1.44 on speaking_rate_adaptation, and\n803\t−0.80 or lower on three further dimensions (overall_fidelity, accent_dialect_handling, entity_\n804\tpronunciation). Three dimensions (audio_clarity, speaking_rate_adaptation, overall_fidelity) fall\n805\tbelow the 60% within-1 threshold as a direct consequence, most severely audio_clarity at 34.9%,\n806\twhere humans and Gemini 2.5 Flash both rate the same sessions 4–5 on average (Table 5) while\n807\tGemini 3.1 Pro Preview rates them 2.81 on average. This is a calibration offset, not a ranking fail-\n808\ture: the model still orders sessions in roughly the same relative order as humans on this dimension\n809\t(ρLH = +0.20, comparable to Gemini 2.5 Flash’s +0.25 and Gemini 3.5 Flash’s +0.21); it simply\n810\tanchors its scale lower. Section 5 discusses the deployment implication.\n811\t   Table 3 in the main text (Section 4.6) summarises the headline counts across all three models.\n812\t\n813\t\n814\t\n815\t                                                     19\n816\t\f            Dimension                    ρHH      ρLH    Gap     L%1 Mean L Mean H      Bias\n817\t            accent_dialect_handling      +0.08   +0.17    0.09   76.6%   4.08    4.88   −0.80\n818\t            audio_clarity                +0.47   +0.20    0.27   34.9%   2.81    4.33   −1.52\n819\t            speech_clarity               +0.01   +0.03    0.01   86.1%   4.68    4.43   +0.25\n820\t            entity_pronunciation         +0.09   +0.08    0.00   61.2%   3.91    4.71   −0.80\n821\t            prosody_naturalness          +0.11   +0.16    0.05   67.0%   3.39    3.94   −0.55\n822\t            interruption_audio_quality   +0.25   +0.41    0.17   71.8%   3.34    3.20   +0.15\n823\t            speaking_rate_adaptation     +0.17   +0.21    0.05   37.3%   2.59    4.03   −1.44\n824\t            overall_fidelity             +0.11   +0.12    0.01   52.6%   3.54    4.38   −0.85\n825\t\n826\t      Table 7: Per-dimension agreement for gemini-3.1-pro-preview on the same n = 209 session\n827\t      pool, directly comparable to Table 5 and Table 6. Column definitions match Table 6. Source:\n828\t      h1_per_dim_gemini31propreview.csv.\n829\t\n830\t\n831\tB.3    Complete 48-cell defect-recall table\n832\tTable 8 is the full data behind the forest plot in Figure 4 of the main paper. L rec and H rec are the\n833\tLALM and human recall (proportion of perturbed clips where the respective judge’s score drops\n834\tby ≥ 1 point relative to baseline); ∆ is L rec − H rec; Sig flags cells whose Newcombe-Wilson 95%\n835\tCI on ∆ excludes zero. Source: h3_defect_recall_with_ci.csv.\n836\t   Of 48 cells, 4 are significantly ∆ > 0 (L>H), 3 are significantly ∆ < 0 (H>L), and 41 have CIs\n837\tthat include zero.\n838\t\n839\tB.4    Per-rater breakdown\n840\tTable 9 shows each rater’s mean per dimension and each pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ. Rater\n841\tlabels are anonymised as R1, R2, R3. Source: h1_per_dim.csv.\n842\t   Rater-mean spread on the same dimension reaches 1.11 points on speech_clarity (R1 3.74 vs R3\n843\t4.85) and 1.12 points on audio_clarity (R1 3.66 vs R2 4.78). This variance underlies the observation\n844\tin Section 4.4 that the LALM’s consistent ratings land closer to the across-rater mean than any\n845\tsingle rater’s ratings do to another rater’s on many dimensions.\n846\t\n847\tB.5    Per-stratum breakdown\n848\tTable 10 summarises LALM-vs-human agreement per stratum for the two most illustrative dimen-\n849\tsions: audio_clarity, where humans show real rank-discrimination (Section 4.1), and accent_\n850\tdialect_handling, which sits near the top of the scale (Section 4.5). The full 14-stratum ×\n851\t8-dimension table is available in h2_per_config_per_dim.csv.\n852\t\n853\tB.6    Score-region partition\n854\tTable 11 partitions each dimension by mean-human rating into ceiling (H̄ ≥ 4), midrange (2.5 ≤\n855\tH̄ < 4), and below (H̄ < 2.5) buckets and re-computes LALM-vs-mean-human ρ within each region.\n856\tOn most dimensions, the below-ceiling bucket is empty because raters rarely use the bottom of the\n857\tscale; the two dimensions with substantive below-ceiling samples show sharply different behaviour,\n858\tdiscussed in the main text (Sections 4.1 and 4.4). Source: e_ceiling_collapse.csv.\n859\t\n860\t\n861\t\n862\t                                                     20\n863\t\f      Defect                 Dimension                    n L rec H rec        ∆ Sig\n864\t      clip                   accent_dialect_handling      7   0.14   0.00   +0.14\n865\t      clip                   audio_clarity                8   0.00   1.00   −1.00 H>L\n866\t      clip                   entity_pronunciation         8   0.12   0.00   +0.12\n867\t      clip                   interruption_audio_quality   8   0.50   0.12   +0.38\n868\t      clip                 