e human panel; negative means the humans are.\n915\t\n916\t\n917\t\n918\t\n919\t                                            21\n920\t\f      Dimension                     R1 mean R2 mean R3 mean                      ρ12     ρ13         ρ23\n921\t      audio_clarity                        3.66          4.78         4.56   +0.45     +0.42    +0.54\n922\t      interruption_audio_quality           3.43          2.24         3.92   +0.20     +0.13    +0.41\n923\t      speaking_rate_adaptation             4.00          4.44         3.66   +0.12     +0.12    +0.25\n924\t      accent_dialect_handling              4.95          4.98         4.70   −0.02     +0.17    +0.09\n925\t      entity_pronunciation                 4.37          4.85         4.91   +0.11     +0.14    +0.01\n926\t      speech_clarity                       3.74          4.71         4.85   −0.03     +0.12    −0.05\n927\t      overall_fidelity                     3.83          4.68         4.64   +0.11     +0.08    +0.13\n928\t      prosody_naturalness                  3.56          4.60         3.67   +0.07     +0.19    +0.05\n929\t\n930\tTable 9: Per-rater means and pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ across the 209-session pool.\n931\tR1, R2, R3 are anonymous rater identifiers.\n932\t\n933\t                                        audio_clarity accent_dialect_handling\n934\t              Stratum              n     ρLH̄     L%1         ρLH̄                     L%1\n935\t              clean-american-1     10   +0.09      100       —                          100\n936\t              clean-american-2     38   +0.21       95    −0.14                          95\n937\t              clean-indian         10   −0.54       90    +0.60                          90\n938\t              clean-british        10   −0.06       90    −0.11                         100\n939\t              clean-french         10   −0.32       90    +0.68                          90\n940\t              codec-american-1      9      —       100       —                          100\n941\t              codec-american-2     10   −0.07      100       —                          100\n942\t              codec-indian         10   −0.11       90    −0.41                          90\n943\t              codec-indian-2       10   −0.27       80    −0.10                          80\n944\t              codec-british        10   +0.07       90       —                          100\n945\t              codec-french         10   +0.51      100    +0.78                         100\n946\t              codec-italian        10   +0.04      100    −0.27                         100\n947\t              adversarial          57   +0.56       79    −0.18                          88\n948\t\n949\tTable 10: Per-stratum LALM-vs-human agreement on two representative dimensions. Here\n950\tρLH̄ is the Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating (distinct\n951\tfrom ρLH in Table 5, which averages the three LALM-vs-individual -rater correlations);\n952\tper-stratum n is too small to compute the three-pair average reliably. Small per-cell n\n953\t(typically 10) inflates the CI on per-stratum ρ; per-stratum numbers should be treated as\n954\tindicative rather than definitive. A dash (—) marks cells where ρ is undefined because the\n955\tLALM assigned a constant rating within the stratum (zero rank variance).\n956\t\n957\t                                         Ceiling (H̄ ≥ 4) Midrange Below (H̄ < 2.5)\n958\t         Dimension                        n            ρLH̄      n   ρLH̄    n                ρLH̄\n959\t         entity_pronunciation            191       +0.23 18 +0.36 0                          —\n960\t         speech_clarity                  185       +0.04 24 +0.07 0                          —\n961\t         prosody_naturalness             125       +0.03 82 −0.05 2                          —\n962\t         overall_fidelity                176       +0.01 32 −0.53 1                          —\n963\t         interruption_audio_quality       56       +0.08 105 +0.01 48                     −0.06\n964\t         speaking_rate_adaptation        139       +0.21 69 +0.19 1                          —\n965\t         accent_dialect_handling         203       +0.00   6    — 0                          —\n966\t         audio_clarity                   182       −0.03 17 −0.37 10                      +0.67\n967\t\n968\tTable 11: LALM-human Spearman ρ partitioned by mean-human rating region. Empty cells\n969\tindicate the region has zero eligible sessions for that dimension.\n970\t\n971\t\n972\t\n973\t\n974\t                                                  22\n975\t\fB.7    Persona vs codec effect deltas\n976\tTable 12 decomposes the codec-degradation-arm rating shifts into their persona and codec compo-\n977\tnents. Codecavg is the mean rating change from codec on/off averaging over both accents; Persona\n978\tis the codec-on rating difference between codec-american-1 (barge-in) and codec-american-2\n979\t(dual-conversation), which share the broad American accent family and codec setting but differ in\n980\tpersona; we note the persona effect is not fully isolated from the American-1/American-2 accent\n981\tdifference, so this decomposition is indicative rather than a clean persona contrast. Neutral baseline\n982\tis the same-persona same-codec across-accent delta as a chance floor. Source: d_personality_vs_\n983\tcodec.csv.\n984\t\n985\t                        Dimension                    Codecavg Persona Neutral\n986\t                        entity_pronunciation              −0.16   +0.73    −0.05\n987\t                        speech_clarity                    −0.17   +0.08    +0.05\n988\t                        prosody_naturalness               −0.13   −0.47    −0.12\n989\t                        overall_fidelity                  +0.09   −0.02    −0.20\n990\t                        interruption_audio_quality        +0.15   −0.70    +0.25\n991\t                        speaking_rate_adaptation          −0.24   −0.38    −0.09\n992\t                        accent_dialect_handling            0.00   −0.04    +0.04\n993\t                        audio_clarity                     −0.15   −0.12    −0.05\n994\t                        | · | mean                        0.14    0.32      0.11\n995\t\n996\t      Table 12: Persona-vs-codec effect decomposition. Persona effect / codec effect ratio averaged\n997\t      across the eight dimensions is 2.3; both exceed the neutral baseline of 0.11.\n998\t\n999\t\n1000\t\n1001\tC     DSP Defect Implementations\n1002\tC.1    Parameter table\n1003\tTable 13 lists the parameter values used for each of the six adversarial defects. Each defect is applied\n1004\tto an isolated copy of the baseline WAV; the perturbed clip is then re-registered as a synthetic run\n1005\tin the evaluation backend and scored by both the LALM and the three human raters.\n1006\t\n1007\tC.2    Reference implementation\n1008\tThe six defects are implemented as pure-Python functions taking a NumPy array of the stereo\n1009\tsignal and returning a modified array of the same shape (except truncate_utterance, which\n1010\treturns a shorter array). Illustrative implementations for the four signal-domain defects (the two\n1011\ttemporal-splicing defects are more verbose) are:\n1012\t\n1013\timport numpy as np\n1014\t\n1015\tSR = 16000\n1016\tAGENT = 0 # LEFT channel (agent); RIGHT (1) is the client\n1017\t\n1018\tdef clip(x, thr=0.85):\n1019\t\n1020\t\n1021\t                                                     23\n1022\t\f     Defect                    Parameter values\n1023\t     clip                      Hard amplitude clipping at ±0.85 of peak amplitude applied to the agent\n1024\t                               (LEFT) channel; both channels’ peaks are preserved before clipping.\n1025\t                               Duration unchanged.\n1026\t     dead_air                  A single random 200–800 ms silence inserted into the agent channel\n1027\t                               at a uniformly-random position between 20% and 80% of the session\n1028\t                               duration. Client channel unmodified in the same time window.\n1029\t     snr_noise                 Additive Gaussian white noise scaled to yield SNR of −2 to −8 dB\n1030\t                               (uniformly sampled per session) relative to the loudest 500 ms window\n1031\t                               of the agent channel. Applied to both channels.\n1032\t     sample_rate_mismatch      Downsample the agent channel from 16 kHz to 8 kHz then upsample back\n1033\t                               to 16 kHz using linear interpolation; introduces characteristic aliasing\n1034\t                               artefacts. Duration and RMS preserved.\n1035\t     truncate_utterance        A single 150–400 ms segment of the agent channel is removed at a\n1036\t                               uniformly-random position between 30% and 70% of the session du-\n1037\t                               ration. The tail is spliced back with a 5 ms linear crossfade. Session\n1038\t                               duration reduced by the truncation length.\n1039\t     mispronounce_overdub      A short vowel-region segment (100–300 ms) in the agent channel is re-\n1040\t                               placed with a length-matched vowel from a different phoneme drawn\n1041\t                               from a small candidate pool. Duration unchanged.\n1042\t\n1043\t     Table 13: Adversarial defect parameters. All defects operate on the 16 kHz stereo WAV\n1044\t     baselines and preserve total duration except where noted.\n1045\t\n1046\t\n1047\t   \"\"\"Hard-clip the agent channel to a fraction of its peak.\"\"\"\n1048\t   y = x.copy()\n1049\t   peak = np.max(np.abs(y[:, AGENT]))\n1050\t   y[:, AGENT] = np.clip(y[:, AGENT], -thr * peak, thr * peak)\n1051\t   return y\n1052\t\n1053\tdef snr_noise(x, snr_db):\n1054\t    \"\"\"Add Gaussian noise at a target SNR (dB), relative to the\n1055\t    loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel; noise on both.\"\"\"\n1056\t    agent = x[:, AGENT]\n1057\t    win = int(0.5 * SR)\n1058\t    energy = np.convolve(agent ** 2, np.ones(win), mode=\"valid\")\n1059\t    start = int(np.argmax(energy))\n1060\t    peak_rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(agent[start:start + win] ** 2))\n1061\t    noise_rms = peak_rms / (10 ** (snr_db / 20))\n1062\t    return x + np.random.normal(0, noise_rms, size=x.shape)\n1063\t\n1064\tdef sample_rate_mismatch(x):\n1065\t    \"\"\"8 kHz down/up-sample of the agent channel (linear interp).\"\"\"\n1066\t    y = x.copy()\n1067\t\n1068\t\n1069\t\n1070\t                                                  24\n1071\t\f      agent = y[:, AGENT]\n1072\t      down = agent[np.arange(0, len(agent), 2)]\n1073\t      y[:, AGENT] = np.interp(np.arange(len(agent)),\n1074\t                              np.arange(len(down)) * 2, down)\n1075\t      return y\n1076\t\n1077\tdef dead_air(x, start_s, dur_s):\n1078\t    \"\"\"Zero-fill a window on the agent channel.\"\"\"\n1079\t    y = x.copy()\n1080\t    s, e = int(start_s * SR), int((start_s + dur_s) * SR)\n1081\t    y[s:e, AGENT] = 0.0\n1082\t    return y\n1083\t\n1084\t   Truncation and mispronounce-overdub are implemented as splice-and-crossfade over source-and-\n1085\tdonor phoneme regions; the full implementations are available in the reproducibility manifest (Ap-\n1086\tpendix E).\n1087\t\n1088\t\n1089\tD     Statistical Methodology\n1090\tD.1    Krippendorff α with ordinal weighting\n1091\tWe compute α with the ordinal difference function of Krippendorff [6], in which the disagreement\n1092\tbetween two ordinal ratings is a rank-based squared distance defined over the cumulative marginal\n1093\tcategory frequencies (not the raw squared difference (v1 −v2 )2 , which is the interval metric). We use\n1094\tthe reference krippendorff implementation. Values are reported in the main paper’s Table 1 as\n1095\tthe “Krip. α” column. We warn readers that on ceiling-effect dimensions the observed disagreement\n1096\tapproaches the expected chance disagreement, driving α toward zero, or slightly negative, regardless\n1097\tof the high simple agreement on the same dimension.\n1098\t\n1099\tD.2    Newcombe-Wilson hybrid CIs on recall difference\n1100\tFor each (defect, dimension) cell we form the LALM recall p̂L = kL /n and human recall p̂H = kH /n,\n1101\twhere kL and kH are the counts of perturbed clips where the respective judge’s score drops by ≥ 1\n1102\tpoint relative to baseline and n is the number of three-rater-covered perturbed clips for that cell.\n1103\tWe compute the 95% CI on p̂L − p̂H using Newcombe’s Method 10 (hybrid Wilson), which for two\n1104\tindependent proportions combines the Wilson score CIs on each proportion into a lower bound L\n1105\tand upper bound U on the difference (see Newcombe [4], eqs. 12–14). A cell is flagged L>H when\n1106\tL > 0 and H>L when U < 0.\n1107\t\n1108\tD.3    Paired-test robustness check\n1109\tNewcombe’s Method 10 treats the LALM and human recalls as two independent proportions, but\n1110\tthey are in fact paired: both judges score the same perturbed clips. As a robustness check we\n1111\tre-tested each cell with an exact paired McNemar test on the per-clip discordant pairs (the clips\n1112\t\n1113\t                                                  25\n1114\t\fone judge flags and the other does not). Under this stricter paired criterion, 2 of the 48 cells reach\n1115\tp < 0.05, both in the Human>LALM direction and both perfect 8-of-8-versus-0-of-8 splits: clip ×\n1116\taudio_clarity and snr_noise × entity_pronunciation. The other five cells the Newcombe-Wilson\n1117\tintervals flagged do not survive the paired test at n ≤ 8: three of the five have a 5-of-5 (or 5-of-7)\n1118\tdiscordant split, i.e. every discordant pair favors the same judge, but at this sample size an exact\n1119\tbinomial test needs a perfectly unanimous split to clear p < 0.05, so these read as underpowered\n1120\tdirectional misses rather than disconfirmed effects. This reinforces the main-text caution that the\n1121\tindividual significant cells are hypotheses to confirm rather than established effects; only the two\n1122\tmost extreme misses are robust to the paired analysis.\n1123\t\n1124\tD.4    Bootstrap parameters\n1125\tConfidence intervals on Spearman ρ between the LALM and each rater use non-parametric boot-\n1126\tstrap with the following parameters:\n1127\t\n1128\t• Iterations: 1,000\n1129\t• Resampling unit: session (i.e. all 8 dimensions of a resampled session travel together)\n1130\t• Sampling: with replacement\n1131\t• CI method: percentile (2.5%, 97.5%)\n1132\t• Random seed: 42 (documented in the analysis script)\n1133\t\n1134\tD.5    Human-human ρ confidence intervals\n1135\tSection 4.1 compares the bootstrap 95% CI of the LALM-human ρ (Table 5) against the CI of the\n1136\thuman-human ρ, which is not tabulated elsewhere in this paper. Table 14 reports it, computed with\n1137\tthe identical session-level resampling procedure described above, applied to the average of the three\n1138\tpairwise rater-rater correlations. On 7 of 8 dimensions the two intervals overlap; on audio_clarity\n1139\tthey do not, which is why that dimension’s rank-correlation gap is treated as the one exception to\n1140\tthe LALM-as-fourth-rater parity result. Source: rho_hh_ci.csv.\n1141\t\n1142\t            Dimension                    ρHH     95% CI (ρHH )     95% CI (ρLH )     Overlap\n1143\t            accent_dialect_handling      +0.08    [−0.01, +0.29]    [−0.12, +0.17]   yes\n1144\t            audio_clarity                +0.47    [+0.34, +0.58]    [+0.00, +0.30]   no\n1145\t            speech_clarity               +0.01    [−0.05, +0.08]    [+0.04, +0.33]   yes\n1146\t            entity_pronunciation         +0.09    [−0.00, +0.21]    [+0.04, +0.32]   yes\n1147\t            prosody_naturalness          +0.11    [+0.02, +0.20]    [+0.03, +0.28]   yes\n1148\t            interruption_audio_quality   +0.25    [+0.16, +0.34]    [+0.03, +0.29]   yes\n1149\t            speaking_rate_adaptation     +0.17    [+0.08, +0.26]    [+0.02, +0.26]   yes\n1150\t            overall_fidelity             +0.11    [+0.02, +0.20]    [−0.13, +0.15]   yes\n1151\t\n1152\t      Table 14: Bootstrap 95% confidence intervals on the human-human ρ (average of the three\n1153\t      pairwise rater correlations) alongside the LALM-human ρ CI already reported in Table 5.\n1154\t      Both use the same 1,000-iteration, session-level, seed-42 procedure.\n1155\t\n1156\t\n1157\t\n1158\t\n1159\t                                                  26\n1160\t\fD.6    Pre-registration status\n1161\tNone of the analyses in this paper were pre-registered. The three-regime taxonomy, the LALM-\n1162\tas-fourth-rater test, and the adversarial-defect design were specified before data collection. The\n1163\tpersona-vs-codec decomposition and the per-rater-idiosyncrasy observation were identified post-\n1164\thoc during analysis; the paper treats them as observational. The specific 0.07 rank-correlation-gap\n1165\tthreshold used to report “5 of 8 dimensions” in Section 4.1 was likewise chosen after inspecting the\n1166\tdata (it falls in an observed gap between the fifth- and sixth-closest dimensions, 0.07 versus 0.12)\n1167\trather than fixed in advance; Table 5 reports the full per-dimension gaps so a reader can apply a\n1168\tdifferent threshold if preferred.\n1169\t\n1170\t\n1171\tE     Reproducibility Manifest\n1172\tAnalysis artefacts. Every table in this paper is derived from one of the thirteen CSV files listed\n1173\tbelow. File names refer to the layout of the supplementary archive that accompanies this paper on\n1174\tsubmission.\n1175\t\n1176\t                      File                                Sourced tables\n1177\t\n1178\t                      h1_per_dim.csv                      Tables 5, 9\n1179\t                      h1_per_dim_natural.csv              Table 2\n1180\t                      h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv        Table 6\n1181\t                      h1_per_dim_gemini31propreview.csv   Table 7\n1182\t                      cross_model_comparison.csv          Table 3\n1183\t                      rho_hh_ci.csv                       Table 14\n1184\t                      lalm_as_4th_rater.csv               Table 5, Fig. 3\n1185\t                      h2_per_config_per_dim.csv           Table 10\n1186\t                      h3_defect_recall_with_ci.csv        Table 8, Fig. 4\n1187\t                      e_ceiling_collapse.csv              Table 11\n1188\t                      d_personality_vs_codec.csv          Table 12\n1189\t                      full_per_session.csv                raw per-session ratings\n1190\t                      h3_defect_recall_3rater.csv         pre-CI defect counts\n1191\t\n1192\t\n1193\tPrompt and schema source files. The LALM prompts (Appendix A.4) and their JSON\n1194\tschemas are reproduced verbatim from two production source files: speech_fidelity_prompt.py\n1195\t(AgentSpeechFidelity) and conversational_audio_quality.py (ConversationalAudioQuality).\n1196\tBoth files are included in the supplementary archive.\n1197\t\n1198\t\n1199\tData availability. The anonymised CSVs, LALM prompts, JSON schemas, analysis scripts, and\n1200\trendered figures described above are publicly available as a Hugging Face Dataset at https://\n1201\thuggingface.co/datasets/armaan-sayyad/lalm-judge-validation-full-duplex [7], released\n1202\tunder CC-BY-4.0 for the data and figures and Apache License 2.0 for the scripts and prompts.\n1203\tRater identifiers in the raw CSVs have been anonymised to R1, R2, R3 and session identifiers\n1204\thave been replaced with stable hashes. Every headline number in the paper can be reproduced\n1205\t\n1206\t\n1207\t                                                27\n1208\t\ffrom the released CSVs using the accompanying scripts. The 60 perturbed adversarial clips (short,\n1209\tderivative WAVs) will be included in a subsequent v0.2 release pending final data-clearance review.\n1210\tRaw session recordings from the primary 209-session corpus will not be publicly released, as they\n1211\tcontain production agent output governed by internal data-handling policy. Requests for restricted\n1212\taccess from bona fide researchers will be considered on a case-by-case basis.\n1213\t\n1214\t\n1215\tF    Notation Glossary\n1216\t• LALM: Large Audio Language Model (Gemini 2.5 Flash in this study).\n1217\t• ρHH : pairwise human-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three rater pairs.\n1218\t• ρLH : LALM-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three (LALM, rater) pairs.\n1219\t  Used in Appendix Table 5 and the LALM-as-fourth-rater comparison.\n1220\t• ρLH̄ : Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating H̄ (a single series,\n1221\t  not an average of pairwise correlations). Used for the per-stratum and score-region tables, where\n1222\t  per-cell n is too small to average three pairwise correlations reliably.\n1223\t• H̄: across-rater mean of the three human ratings on a session × dimension.\n1224\t• % within 1: proportion of sessions where the two ratings being compared differ by at most 1\n1225\t  Likert point.\n1226\t• recall (adversarial arm): proportion of perturbed clips where the score drops by at least 1\n1227\t  point relative to the same clip’s baseline rating.\n1228\t• L>H / H>L: significance flag on a (defect, dimension) cell where the LALM (respectively\n1229\t  humans) are more sensitive under a Newcombe-Wilson 95% CI on the recall difference.\n1230\t\n1231\t\n1232\t\n1233\t\n1234\t                                                28\n1235\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bebf14cbf30df856", "session_id": "2323bd30-3aaf-46fe-8f3f-f54d2b380792", "uuid": "d75084fb-8bdb-490e-950f-674486455520", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T14:50:19.883Z"}
