|\n424\t| snr_noise | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.00 | 1.00 | −1.00 | H>L |\n425\t| snr_noise | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 1.00 | 0.62 | +0.38 | |\n426\t| snr_noise | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.88 | 1.00 | −0.12 | |\n427\t| snr_noise | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.88 | 0.62 | +0.25 | |\n428\t| snr_noise | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n429\t| snr_noise | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.88 | 0.88 | 0.00 | |\n430\t| truncate_utterance | accent_dialect_handling | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n431\t| truncate_utterance | audio_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n432\t| truncate_utterance | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n433\t| truncate_utterance | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 0.62 | 0.00 | +0.62 | L>H |\n434\t| truncate_utterance | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.38 | 0.00 | +0.38 | |\n435\t| truncate_utterance | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.38 | 0.00 | +0.38 | |\n436\t| truncate_utterance | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n437\t| truncate_utterance | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n438\t\n439\tPositive Δ means the LALM is more sensitive to the defect than the human panel; negative means the humans are.\n440\t\n441\t**B.4 Per-rater breakdown**\n442\t\n443\tTable 9 shows each rater's mean per dimension and each pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ. Rater labels are anonymised as R1, R2, R3. Source: h1_per_dim.csv.\n444\t\n445\tRater-mean spread on the same dimension reaches 1.11 points on speech_clarity (R1 3.74 vs R3 4.85) and 1.12 points on audio_clarity (R1 3.66 vs R2 4.78). This variance underlies the observation in Section 4.4 that the LALM's consistent ratings land closer to the across-rater mean than any single rater's ratings do to another rater's on many dimensions.\n446\t\n447\t**Table 9: Per-rater means and pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ across the 209-session pool**\n448\t\n449\t| Dimension | R1 mean | R2 mean | R3 mean | ρ12 | ρ13 | ρ23 |\n450\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n451\t| audio_clarity | 3.66 | 4.78 | 4.56 | +0.45 | +0.42 | +0.54 |\n452\t| interruption_audio_quality | 3.43 | 2.24 | 3.92 | +0.20 | +0.13 | +0.41 |\n453\t| speaking_rate_adaptation | 4.00 | 4.44 | 3.66 | +0.12 | +0.12 | +0.25 |\n454\t| accent_dialect_handling | 4.95 | 4.98 | 4.70 | −0.02 | +0.17 | +0.09 |\n455\t| entity_pronunciation | 4.37 | 4.85 | 4.91 | +0.11 | +0.14 | +0.01 |\n456\t| speech_clarity | 3.74 | 4.71 | 4.85 | −0.03 | +0.12 | −0.05 |\n457\t| overall_fidelity | 3.83 | 4.68 | 4.64 | +0.11 | +0.08 | +0.13 |\n458\t| prosody_naturalness | 3.56 | 4.60 | 3.67 | +0.07 | +0.19 | +0.05 |\n459\t\n460\t**B.5 Per-stratum breakdown**\n461\t\n462\tTable 10 summarises LALM-vs-human agreement per stratum for the two most illustrative dimensions: audio_clarity, where humans show real rank-discrimination (Section 4.1), and accent_dialect_handling, which sits near the top of the scale (Section 4.5). The full 14-stratum × 8-dimension table is available in h2_per_config_per_dim.csv.\n463\t\n464\t**Table 10: Per-stratum LALM-vs-human agreement on two representative dimensions**\n465\t\n466\t| Stratum | n | ρLH̄ (audio_clarity) | L%1 (audio_clarity) | ρLH̄ (accent_dialect_handling) | L%1 (accent_dialect_handling) |\n467\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n468\t| clean-american-1 | 10 | +0.09 | 100 | — | 100 |\n469\t| clean-american-2 | 38 | +0.21 | 95 | −0.14 | 95 |\n470\t| clean-indian | 10 | −0.54 | 90 | +0.60 | 90 |\n471\t| clean-british | 10 | −0.06 | 90 | −0.11 | 100 |\n472\t| clean-french | 10 | −0.32 | 90 | +0.68 | 90 |\n473\t| codec-american-1 | 9 | — | 100 | — | 100 |\n474\t| codec-american-2 | 10 | −0.07 | 100 | — | 100 |\n475\t| codec-indian | 10 | −0.11 | 90 | −0.41 | 90 |\n476\t| codec-indian-2 | 10 | −0.27 | 80 | −0.10 | 80 |\n477\t| codec-british | 10 | +0.07 | 90 | — | 100 |\n478\t| codec-french | 10 | +0.51 | 100 | +0.78 | 100 |\n479\t| codec-italian | 10 | +0.04 | 100 | −0.27 | 100 |\n480\t| adversarial | 57 | +0.56 | 79 | −0.18 | 88 |\n481\t\n482\tρLH̄ is the Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating (distinct from ρLH in Table 5, which averages the three LALM-vs-individual-rater correlations); per-stratum n is too small to compute the three-pair average reliably. Small per-cell n (typically 10) inflates the CI on per-stratum ρ; per-stratum numbers should be treated as indicative rather than definitive. A dash (—) marks cells where ρ is undefined because the LALM assigned a constant rating within the stratum (zero rank variance).\n483\t\n484\t**B.6 Score-region partition**\n485\t\n486\tTable 11 partitions each dimension by mean-human rating into ceiling (H̄ ≥ 4), midrange (2.5 ≤ H̄ < 4), and below (H̄ < 2.5) buckets and re-computes LALM-vs-mean-human ρ within each region. On most dimensions, the below-ceiling bucket is empty because raters rarely use the bottom of the scale; the two dimensions with substantive below-ceiling samples show sharply different behaviour, discussed in the main text (Sections 4.1 and 4.4). Source: e_ceiling_collapse.csv.\n487\t\n488\t**Table 11: LALM-human Spearman ρ partitioned by mean-human rating region**\n489\t\n490\t| Dimension | Ceiling n | Ceiling ρLH̄ | Midrange n | Midrange ρLH̄ | Below n | Below ρLH̄ |\n491\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n492\t| entity_pronunciation | 191 | +0.23 | 18 | +0.36 | 0 | — |\n493\t| speech_clarity | 185 | +0.04 | 24 | +0.07 | 0 | — |\n494\t| prosody_naturalness | 125 | +0.03 | 82 | −0.05 | 2 | — |\n495\t| overall_fidelity | 176 | +0.01 | 32 | −0.53 | 1 | — |\n496\t| interruption_audio_quality | 56 | +0.08 | 105 | +0.01 | 48 | −0.06 |\n497\t| speaking_rate_adaptation | 139 | +0.21 | 69 | +0.19 | 1 | — |\n498\t| accent_dialect_handling | 203 | +0.00 | 6 | — | 0 | — |\n499\t| audio_clarity | 182 | −0.03 | 17 | −0.37 | 10 | +0.67 |\n500\t\n501\tEmpty cells indicate the region has zero eligible sessions for that dimension.\n502\t\n503\t**B.7 Persona vs codec effect deltas**\n504\t\n505\tTable 12 decomposes the codec-degradation-arm rating shifts into their persona and codec components. Codec_avg is the mean rating change from codec on/off averaging over both accents; Persona is the codec-on rating difference between codec-american-1 (barge-in) and codec-american-2 (dual-conversation), which share the broad American accent family and codec setting but differ in persona; we note the persona effect is not fully isolated from the American-1/American-2 accent difference, so this decomposition is indicative rather than a clean persona contrast. Neutral baseline is the same-persona same-codec across-accent delta as a chance floor. Source: d_personality_vs_codec.csv.\n506\t\n507\t**Table 12: Persona-vs-codec effect decomposition**\n508\t\n509\t| Dimension | Codec_avg | Persona | Neutral |\n510\t|---|---|---|---|\n511\t| entity_pronunciation | −0.16 | +0.73 | −0.05 |\n512\t| speech_clarity | −0.17 | +0.08 | +0.05 |\n513\t| prosody_naturalness | −0.13 | −0.47 | −0.12 |\n514\t| overall_fidelity | +0.09 | −0.02 | −0.20 |\n515\t| interruption_audio_quality | +0.15 | −0.70 | +0.25 |\n516\t| speaking_rate_adaptation | −0.24 | −0.38 | −0.09 |\n517\t| accent_dialect_handling | 0.00 | −0.04 | +0.04 |\n518\t| audio_clarity | −0.15 | −0.12 | −0.05 |\n519\t| | · | mean | 0.14 | 0.32 | 0.11 |\n520\t\n521\tPersona effect / codec effect ratio averaged across the eight dimensions is 2.3; both exceed the neutral baseline of 0.11.\n522\t\n523\t**C DSP Defect Implementations**\n524\t\n525\t**C.1 Parameter table**\n526\t\n527\tTable 13 lists the parameter values used for each of the six adversarial defects. Each defect is applied to an isolated copy of the baseline WAV; the perturbed clip is then re-registered as a synthetic run in the evaluation backend and scored by both the LALM and the three human raters.\n528\t\n529\t**Table 13: Adversarial defect parameters**\n530\t\n531\t| Defect | Parameter values |\n532\t|---|---|\n533\t| clip | Hard amplitude clipping at ±0.85 of peak amplitude applied to the agent (LEFT) channel; both channels' peaks are preserved before clipping. Duration unchanged. |\n534\t| dead_air | A single random 200–800 ms silence inserted into the agent channel at a uniformly-random position between 20% and 80% of the session duration. Client channel unmodified in the same time window. |\n535\t| snr_noise | Additive Gaussian white noise scaled to yield SNR of −2 to −8 dB (uniformly sampled per session) relative to the loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel. Applied to both channels. |\n536\t| sample_rate_mismatch | Downsample the agent channel from 16 kHz to 8 kHz then upsample back to 16 kHz using linear interpolation; introduces characteristic aliasing artefacts. Duration and RMS preserved. |\n537\t| truncate_utterance | A single 150–400 ms segment of the agent channel is removed at a uniformly-random position between 30% and 70% of the session duration. The tail is spliced back with a 5 ms linear crossfade. Session duration reduced by the truncation length. |\n538\t| mispronounce_overdub | A short vowel-region segment (100–300 ms) in the agent channel is replaced with a length-matched vowel from a different phoneme drawn from a small candidate pool. Duration unchanged. |\n539\t\n540\tAll defects operate on the 16 kHz stereo WAV baselines and preserve total duration except where noted.\n541\t\n542\t**C.2 Reference implementation**\n543\t\n544\tThe six defects are implemented as pure-Python functions taking a NumPy array of the stereo signal and returning a modified array of the same shape (except truncate_utterance, which returns a shorter array). Illustrative implementations for the four signal-domain defects (the two temporal-splicing defects are more verbose) are:\n545\t\n546\t```python\n547\timport numpy as np\n548\t\n549\tSR = 16000\n550\tAGENT = 0  # LEFT channel (agent); RIGHT (1) is the client\n551\t\n552\tdef clip(x, thr=0.85):\n553\t    \"\"\"Hard-clip the agent channel to a fraction of its peak.\"\"\"\n554\t    y = x.copy()\n555\t    peak = np.max(np.abs(y[:, AGENT]))\n556\t    y[:, AGENT] = np.clip(y[:, AGENT], -thr * peak, thr * peak)\n557\t    return y\n558\t\n559\tdef snr_noise(x, snr_db):\n560\t    \"\"\"Add Gaussian noise at a target SNR (dB), relative to the\n561\t    loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel; noise on both.\"\"\"\n562\t    agent = x[:, AGENT]\n563\t    win = int(0.5 * SR)\n564\t    energy = np.convolve(agent ** 2, np.ones(win), mode=\"valid\")\n565\t    start = int(np.argmax(energy))\n566\t    peak_rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(agent[start:start + win] ** 2))\n567\t    noise_rms = peak_rms / (10 ** (snr_db / 20))\n568\t    return x + np.random.normal(0, noise_rms, size=x.shape)\n569\t\n570\tdef sample_rate_mismatch(x):\n571\t    \"\"\"8 kHz down/up-sample of the agent channel (linear interp).\"\"\"\n572\t    y = x.copy()\n573\t    agent = y[:, AGENT]\n574\t    down = agent[np.arange(0, len(agent), 2)]\n575\t    y[:, AGENT] = np.interp(np.arange(len(agent)),\n576\t                            np.arange(len(down)) * 2, down)\n577\t    return y\n578\t\n579\tdef dead_air(x, start_s, dur_s):\n580\t    \"\"\"Zero-fill a window on the agent channel.\"\"\"\n581\t    y = x.copy()\n582\t    s, e = int(start_s * SR), int((start_s + dur_s) * SR)\n583\t    y[s:e, AGENT] = 0.0\n584\t    return y\n585\t```\n586\t\n587\tTruncation and mispronounce-overdub are implemented as splice-and-crossfade over source-and-donor phoneme regions; the full implementations are available in the reproducibility manifest (Appendix E).\n588\t\n589\t**D Statistical Methodology**\n590\t\n591\t**D.1 Krippendorff α with ordinal weighting**\n592\t\n593\tWe compute α with the ordinal difference function of Krippendorff [6], in which the disagreement between two ordinal ratings is a rank-based squared distance defined over the cumulative marginal category frequencies (not the raw squared difference (v1 − v2)^2, which is the interval metric). We use the reference krippendorff implementation. Values are reported in the main paper's Table 1 as the \"Krip. α\" column. We warn readers that on ceiling-effect dimensions the observed disagreement approaches the expected chance disagreement, driving α toward zero, or slightly negative, regardless of the high simple agreement on the same dimension.\n594\t\n595\t**D.2 Newcombe-Wilson hybrid CIs on recall difference**\n596\t\n597\tFor each (defect, dimension) cell we form the LALM recall p̂L = kL/n and human recall p̂H = kH/n, where kL and kH are the counts of perturbed clips where the respective judge's score drops by ≥ 1 point relative to baseline and n is the number of three-rater-covered perturbed clips for that cell. We compute the 95% CI on p̂L − p̂H using Newcombe's Method 10 (hybrid Wilson), which for two independent proportions combines the Wilson score CIs on each proportion into a lower bound L and upper bound U on the difference (see Newcombe [4], eqs. 12–14). A cell is flagged L>H when L > 0 and H>L when U < 0.\n598\t\n599\t**D.3 Paired-test robustness check**\n600\t\n601\tNewcombe's Method 10 treats the LALM and human recalls as two independent proportions, but they are in fact paired: both judges score the same perturbed clips. As a robustness check we re-tested each cell with an exact paired McNemar test on the per-clip discordant pairs (the clips one judge flags and the other does not). Under this stricter paired criterion, 2 of the 48 cells reach p < 0.05, both in the Human>LALM direction and both perfect 8-of-8-versus-0-of-8 splits: clip × audio_clarity and snr_noise × entity_pronunciation. The other five cells the Newcombe-Wilson intervals flagged do not survive the paired test at n ≤ 8: three of the five have a 5-of-5 (or 5-of-7) discordant split, i.e. every discordant pair favors the same judge, but at this sample size an exact binomial test needs a perfectly unanimous split to clear p < 0.05, so these read as underpowered directional misses rather than disconfirmed effects. This reinforces the main-text caution that the individual significant cells are hypotheses to confirm rather than established effects; only the two most extreme misses are robust to the paired analysis.\n602\t\n603\t**D.4 Bootstrap parameters**\n604\t\n605\tConfidence intervals on Spearman ρ between the LALM and each rater use non-parametric bootstrap with the following parameters:\n606\t\n607\t- Iterations: 1,000\n608\t- Resampling unit: session (i.e. all 8 dimensions of a resampled session travel together)\n609\t- Sampling: with replacement\n610\t- CI method: percentile (2.5%, 97.5%)\n611\t- Random seed: 42 (documented in the analysis script)\n612\t\n613\t**D.5 Human-human ρ confidence intervals**\n614\t\n615\tSection 4.1 compares the bootstrap 95% CI of the LALM-human ρ (Table 5) against the CI of the human-human ρ, which is not tabulated elsewhere in this paper. Table 14 reports it, computed with the identical session-level resampling procedure described above, applied to the average of the three pairwise rater-rater correlations. On 7 of 8 dimensions the two intervals overlap; on audio_clarity they do not, which is why that dimension's rank-correlation gap is treated as the one exception to the LALM-as-fourth-rater parity result. Source: rho_hh_ci.csv.\n616\t\n617\t**Table 14: Bootstrap 95% confidence intervals on the human-human ρ alongside the LALM-human ρ CI**\n618\t\n619\t| Dimension | ρHH | 95% CI (ρHH) | 95% CI (ρLH) | Overlap |\n620\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n621\t| accent_dialect_handling | +0.08 | [−0.01, +0.29] | [−0.12, +0.17] | yes |\n622\t| audio_clarity | +0.47 | [+0.34, +0.58] | [+0.00, +0.30] | no |\n623\t| speech_clarity | +0.01 | [−0.05, +0.08] | [+0.04, +0.33] | yes |\n624\t| entity_pronunciation | +0.09 | [−0.00, +0.21] | [+0.04, +0.32] | yes |\n625\t| prosody_naturalness | +0.11 | [+0.02, +0.20] | [+0.03, +0.28] | yes |\n626\t| interruption_audio_quality | +0.25 | [+0.16, +0.34] | [+0.03, +0.29] | yes |\n627\t| speaking_rate_adaptation | +0.17 | [+0.08, +0.26] | [+0.02, +0.26] | yes |\n628\t| overall_fidelity | +0.11 | [+0.02, +0.20] | [−0.13, +0.15] | yes |\n629\t\n630\tBoth use the same 1,000-iteration, session-level, seed-42 procedure.\n631\t\n632\t**D.6 Pre-registration status**\n633\t\n634\tNone of the analyses in this paper were pre-registered. The three-regime taxonomy, the LALM-as-fourth-rater test, and the adversarial-defect design were specified before data collection. The persona-vs-codec decomposition and the per-rater-idiosyncrasy observation were identified post-hoc during analysis; the paper treats them as observational. The specific 0.07 rank-correlation-gap threshold used to report \"5 of 8 dimensions\" in Section 4.1 was likewise chosen after inspecting the data (it falls in an observed gap between the fifth- and sixth-closest dimensions, 0.07 versus 0.12) rather than fixed in advance; Table 5 reports the full per-dimension gaps so a reader can apply a different threshold if preferred.\n635\t\n636\t**E Reproducibility Manifest**\n637\t\n638\tAnalysis artefacts. Every table in this paper is derived from one of the thirteen CSV files listed below. File names refer to the layout of the supplementary archive that accompanies this paper on submission.\n639\t\n640\t| File | Sourced tables |\n641\t|---|---|\n642\t| h1_per_dim.csv | Tables 5, 9 |\n643\t| h1_per_dim_natural.csv | Table 2 |\n644\t| h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv | Table 6 |\n645\t| h1_per_dim_gemini31propreview.csv | Table 7 |\n646\t| cross_model_comparison.csv | Table 3 |\n647\t| rho_hh_ci.csv | Table 14 |\n648\t| lalm_as_4th_rater.csv | Table 5, Fig. 3 |\n649\t| h2_per_config_per_dim.csv | Table 10 |\n650\t| h3_defect_recall_with_ci.csv | Table 8, Fig. 4 |\n651\t| e_ceiling_collapse.csv | Table 11 |\n652\t| d_personality_vs_codec.csv | Table 12 |\n653\t| full_per_session.csv | raw per-session ratings |\n654\t| h3_defect_recall_3rater.csv | pre-CI defect counts |\n655\t\n656\tPrompt and schema source files. The LALM prompts (Appendix A.4) and their JSON schemas are reproduced verbatim from two production source files: speech_fidelity_prompt.py (AgentSpeechFidelity) and conversational_audio_quality.py (ConversationalAudioQuality). Both files are included in the supplementary archive.\n657\t\n658\tData availability. The anonymised CSVs, LALM prompts, JSON schemas, analysis scripts, and rendered figures described above are publicly available as a Hugging Face Dataset at https://huggingface.co/datasets/armaan-sayyad/lalm-judge-validation-full-duplex [7], released under CC-BY-4.0 for the data and figures and Apache License 2.0 for the scripts and prompts. Rater identifiers in the raw CSVs have been anonymised to R1, R2, R3 and session identifiers have been replaced with stable hashes. Every headline number in the paper can be reproduced from the released CSVs using the accompanying scripts. The 60 perturbed adversarial clips (short, derivative WAVs) will be included in a subsequent v0.2 release pending final data-clearance review. Raw session recordings from the primary 209-session corpus will not be publicly released, as they contain production agent output governed by internal data-handling policy. Requests for restricted access from bona fide researchers will be considered on a case-by-case basis.\n659\t\n660\t**F Notation Glossary**\n661\t\n662\t- LALM: Large Audio Language Model (Gemini 2.5 Flash in this study).\n663\t- ρHH: pairwise human-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three rater pairs.\n664\t- ρLH: LALM-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three (LALM, rater) pairs. Used in Appendix Table 5 and the LALM-as-fourth-rater comparison.\n665\t- ρLH̄: Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating H̄ (a single series, not an average of pairwise correlations). Used for the per-stratum and score-region tables, where per-cell n is too small to average three pairwise correlations reliably.\n666\t- H̄: across-rater mean of the three human ratings on a session × dimension.\n667\t- % within 1: proportion of sessions where the two ratings being compared differ by at most 1 Likert point.\n668\t- recall (adversarial arm): proportion of perturbed clips where the score drops by at least 1 point relative to the same clip's baseline rating.\n669\t- L>H / H>L: significance flag on a (defect, dimension) cell where the LALM (respectively humans) are more sensitive under a Newcombe-Wilson 95% CI on the recall difference.\n670\t\n671\t---\n672\t\n673\tThat is the complete text of the paper, including all sections (1-8), all appendices (A-F), all 14 tables, all 4 figure descriptions, and all 11 references. The PDF was downloaded from https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.07985v1 (789 KB) and text was extracted using `pdftotext -layout`, yielding 1,234 lines / 82,605 characters of text.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "2323bd30-3aaf-46fe-8f3f-f54d2b380792", "uuid": "996774d7-c254-4dda-acc1-8a2a8f3f9d50", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:06:57.121Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.07985_full.txt", "content": "| dead_air | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n| dead_air | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 0.25 | 0.00 | +0.25 | |\n| dead_air | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.38 | 0.00 | +0.38 | |\n| dead_air | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.25 | 0.12 | +0.12 | |\n| dead_air | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n| dead_air | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.12 | 0.00 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | accent_dialect_handling | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | audio_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.12 | 0.12 | 0.00 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.38 | 0.12 | +0.25 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.38 | 0.12 | +0.25 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.12 | −0.12 | |\n| mispronounce_overdub | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | accent_dialect_handling | 8 | 0.25 | 0.00 | +0.25 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | audio_clarity | 7 | 0.00 | 0.71 | −0.71 | H>L |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | interruption_audio_quality | 7 | 0.43 | 0.00 | +0.43 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.38 | −0.25 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.25 | 0.12 | +0.12 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.25 | −0.25 | |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.25 | −0.12 | |\n| snr_noise | accent_dialect_handling | 8 | 0.62 | 0.00 | +0.62 | L>H |\n| snr_noise | audio_clarity | 8 | 1.00 | 1.00 | 0.00 | |\n| snr_noise | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.00 | 1.00 | −1.00 | H>L |\n| snr_noise | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 1.00 | 0.62 | +0.38 | |\n| snr_noise | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.88 | 1.00 | −0.12 | |\n| snr_noise | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.88 | 0.62 | +0.25 | |\n| snr_noise | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| snr_noise | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.88 | 0.88 | 0.00 | |\n| truncate_utterance | accent_dialect_handling | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| truncate_utterance | audio_clarity | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| truncate_utterance | entity_pronunciation | 8 | 0.12 | 0.00 | +0.12 | |\n| truncate_utterance | interruption_audio_quality | 8 | 0.62 | 0.00 | +0.62 | L>H |\n| truncate_utterance | overall_fidelity | 8 | 0.38 | 0.00 | +0.38 | |\n| truncate_utterance | prosody_naturalness | 8 | 0.38 | 0.00 | +0.38 | |\n| truncate_utterance | speaking_rate_adaptation | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n| truncate_utterance | speech_clarity | 8 | 0.00 | 0.00 | 0.00 | |\n\nPositive Δ means the LALM is more sensitive to the defect than the human panel; negative means the humans are.\n\n**B.4 Per-rater breakdown**\n\nTable 9 shows each rater's mean per dimension and each pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ. Rater labels are anonymised as R1, R2, R3. Source: h1_per_dim.csv.\n\nRater-mean spread on the same dimension reaches 1.11 points on speech_clarity (R1 3.74 vs R3 4.85) and 1.12 points on audio_clarity (R1 3.66 vs R2 4.78). This variance underlies the observation in Section 4.4 that the LALM's consistent ratings land closer to the across-rater mean than any single rater's ratings do to another rater's on many dimensions.\n\n**Table 9: Per-rater means and pairwise rater-rater Spearman ρ across the 209-session pool**\n\n| Dimension | R1 mean | R2 mean | R3 mean | ρ12 | ρ13 | ρ23 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| audio_clarity | 3.66 | 4.78 | 4.56 | +0.45 | +0.42 | +0.54 |\n| interruption_audio_quality | 3.43 | 2.24 | 3.92 | +0.20 | +0.13 | +0.41 |\n| speaking_rate_adaptation | 4.00 | 4.44 | 3.66 | +0.12 | +0.12 | +0.25 |\n| accent_dialect_handling | 4.95 | 4.98 | 4.70 | −0.02 | +0.17 | +0.09 |\n| entity_pronunciation | 4.37 | 4.85 | 4.91 | +0.11 | +0.14 | +0.01 |\n| speech_clarity | 3.74 | 4.71 | 4.85 | −0.03 | +0.12 | −0.05 |\n| overall_fidelity | 3.83 | 4.68 | 4.64 | +0.11 | +0.08 | +0.13 |\n| prosody_naturalness | 3.56 | 4.60 | 3.67 | +0.07 | +0.19 | +0.05 |\n\n**B.5 Per-stratum breakdown**\n\nTable 10 summarises LALM-vs-human agreement per stratum for the two most illustrative dimensions: audio_clarity, where humans show real rank-discrimination (Section 4.1), and accent_dialect_handling, which sits near the top of the scale (Section 4.5). The full 14-stratum × 8-dimension table is available in h2_per_config_per_dim.csv.\n\n**Table 10: Per-stratum LALM-vs-human agreement on two representative dimensions**\n\n| Stratum | n | ρLH̄ (audio_clarity) | L%1 (audio_clarity) | ρLH̄ (accent_dialect_handling) | L%1 (accent_dialect_handling) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| clean-american-1 | 10 | +0.09 | 100 | — | 100 |\n| clean-american-2 | 38 | +0.21 | 95 | −0.14 | 95 |\n| clean-indian | 10 | −0.54 | 90 | +0.60 | 90 |\n| clean-british | 10 | −0.06 | 90 | −0.11 | 100 |\n| clean-french | 10 | −0.32 | 90 | +0.68 | 90 |\n| codec-american-1 | 9 | — | 100 | — | 100 |\n| codec-american-2 | 10 | −0.07 | 100 | — | 100 |\n| codec-indian | 10 | −0.11 | 90 | −0.41 | 90 |\n| codec-indian-2 | 10 | −0.27 | 80 | −0.10 | 80 |\n| codec-british | 10 | +0.07 | 90 | — | 100 |\n| codec-french | 10 | +0.51 | 100 | +0.78 | 100 |\n| codec-italian | 10 | +0.04 | 100 | −0.27 | 100 |\n| adversarial | 57 | +0.56 | 79 | −0.18 | 88 |\n\nρLH̄ is the Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating (distinct from ρLH in Table 5, which averages the three LALM-vs-individual-rater correlations); per-stratum n is too small to compute the three-pair average reliably. Small per-cell n (typically 10) inflates the CI on per-stratum ρ; per-stratum numbers should be treated as indicative rather than definitive. A dash (—) marks cells where ρ is undefined because the LALM assigned a constant rating within the stratum (zero rank variance).\n\n**B.6 Score-region partition**\n\nTable 11 partitions each dimension by mean-human rating into ceiling (H̄ ≥ 4), midrange (2.5 ≤ H̄ < 4), and below (H̄ < 2.5) buckets and re-computes LALM-vs-mean-human ρ within each region. On most dimensions, the below-ceiling bucket is empty because raters rarely use the bottom of the scale; the two dimensions with substantive below-ceiling samples show sharply different behaviour, discussed in the main text (Sections 4.1 and 4.4). Source: e_ceiling_collapse.csv.\n\n**Table 11: LALM-human Spearman ρ partitioned by mean-human rating region**\n\n| Dimension | Ceiling n | Ceiling ρLH̄ | Midrange n | Midrange ρLH̄ | Below n | Below ρLH̄ |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| entity_pronunciation | 191 | +0.23 | 18 | +0.36 | 0 | — |\n| speech_clarity | 185 | +0.04 | 24 | +0.07 | 0 | — |\n| prosody_naturalness | 125 | +0.03 | 82 | −0.05 | 2 | — |\n| overall_fidelity | 176 | +0.01 | 32 | −0.53 | 1 | — |\n| interruption_audio_quality | 56 | +0.08 | 105 | +0.01 | 48 | −0.06 |\n| speaking_rate_adaptation | 139 | +0.21 | 69 | +0.19 | 1 | — |\n| accent_dialect_handling | 203 | +0.00 | 6 | — | 0 | — |\n| audio_clarity | 182 | −0.03 | 17 | −0.37 | 10 | +0.67 |\n\nEmpty cells indicate the region has zero eligible sessions for that dimension.\n\n**B.7 Persona vs codec effect deltas**\n\nTable 12 decomposes the codec-degradation-arm rating shifts into their persona and codec components. Codec_avg is the mean rating change from codec on/off averaging over both accents; Persona is the codec-on rating difference between codec-american-1 (barge-in) and codec-american-2 (dual-conversation), which share the broad American accent family and codec setting but differ in persona; we note the persona effect is not fully isolated from the American-1/American-2 accent difference, so this decomposition is indicative rather than a clean persona contrast. Neutral baseline is the same-persona same-codec across-accent delta as a chance floor. Source: d_personality_vs_codec.csv.\n\n**Table 12: Persona-vs-codec effect decomposition**\n\n| Dimension | Codec_avg | Persona | Neutral |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| entity_pronunciation | −0.16 | +0.73 | −0.05 |\n| speech_clarity | −0.17 | +0.08 | +0.05 |\n| prosody_naturalness | −0.13 | −0.47 | −0.12 |\n| overall_fidelity | +0.09 | −0.02 | −0.20 |\n| interruption_audio_quality | +0.15 | −0.70 | +0.25 |\n| speaking_rate_adaptation | −0.24 | −0.38 | −0.09 |\n| accent_dialect_handling | 0.00 | −0.04 | +0.04 |\n| audio_clarity | −0.15 | −0.12 | −0.05 |\n| | · | mean | 0.14 | 0.32 | 0.11 |\n\nPersona effect / codec effect ratio averaged across the eight dimensions is 2.3; both exceed the neutral baseline of 0.11.\n\n**C DSP Defect Implementations**\n\n**C.1 Parameter table**\n\nTable 13 lists the parameter values used for each of the six adversarial defects. Each defect is applied to an isolated copy of the baseline WAV; the perturbed clip is then re-registered as a synthetic run in the evaluation backend and scored by both the LALM and the three human raters.\n\n**Table 13: Adversarial defect parameters**\n\n| Defect | Parameter values |\n|---|---|\n| clip | Hard amplitude clipping at ±0.85 of peak amplitude applied to the agent (LEFT) channel; both channels' peaks are preserved before clipping. Duration unchanged. |\n| dead_air | A single random 200–800 ms silence inserted into the agent channel at a uniformly-random position between 20% and 80% of the session duration. Client channel unmodified in the same time window. |\n| snr_noise | Additive Gaussian white noise scaled to yield SNR of −2 to −8 dB (uniformly sampled per session) relative to the loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel. Applied to both channels. |\n| sample_rate_mismatch | Downsample the agent channel from 16 kHz to 8 kHz then upsample back to 16 kHz using linear interpolation; introduces characteristic aliasing artefacts. Duration and RMS preserved. |\n| truncate_utterance | A single 150–400 ms segment of the agent channel is removed at a uniformly-random position between 30% and 70% of the session duration. The tail is spliced back with a 5 ms linear crossfade. Session duration reduced by the truncation length. |\n| mispronounce_overdub | A short vowel-region segment (100–300 ms) in the agent channel is replaced with a length-matched vowel from a different phoneme drawn from a small candidate pool. Duration unchanged. |\n\nAll defects operate on the 16 kHz stereo WAV baselines and preserve total duration except where noted.\n\n**C.2 Reference implementation**\n\nThe six defects are implemented as pure-Python functions taking a NumPy array of the stereo signal and returning a modified array of the same shape (except truncate_utterance, which returns a shorter array). Illustrative implementations for the four signal-domain defects (the two temporal-splicing defects are more verbose) are:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\nSR = 16000\nAGENT = 0  # LEFT channel (agent); RIGHT (1) is the client\n\ndef clip(x, thr=0.85):\n    \"\"\"Hard-clip the agent channel to a fraction of its peak.\"\"\"\n    y = x.copy()\n    peak = np.max(np.abs(y[:, AGENT]))\n    y[:, AGENT] = np.clip(y[:, AGENT], -thr * peak, thr * peak)\n    return y\n\ndef snr_noise(x, snr_db):\n    \"\"\"Add Gaussian noise at a target SNR (dB), relative to the\n    loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel; noise on both.\"\"\"\n    agent = x[:, AGENT]\n    win = int(0.5 * SR)\n    energy = np.convolve(agent ** 2, np.ones(win), mode=\"valid\")\n    start = int(np.argmax(energy))\n    peak_rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(agent[start:start + win] ** 2))\n    noise_rms = peak_rms / (10 ** (snr_db / 20))\n    return x + np.random.normal(0, noise_rms, size=x.shape)\n\ndef sample_rate_mismatch(x):\n    \"\"\"8 kHz down/up-sample of the agent channel (linear interp).\"\"\"\n    y = x.copy()\n    agent = y[:, AGENT]\n    down = agent[np.arange(0, len(agent), 2)]\n    y[:, AGENT] = np.interp(np.arange(len(agent)),\n                            np.arange(len(down)) * 2, down)\n    return y\n\ndef dead_air(x, start_s, dur_s):\n    \"\"\"Zero-fill a window on the agent channel.\"\"\"\n    y = x.copy()\n    s, e = int(start_s * SR), int((start_s + dur_s) * SR)\n    y[s:e, AGENT] = 0.0\n    return y\n```\n\nTruncation and mispronounce-overdub are implemented as splice-and-crossfade over source-and-donor phoneme regions; the full implementations are available in the reproducibility manifest (Appendix E).\n\n**D Statistical Methodology**\n\n**D.1 Krippendorff α with ordinal weighting**\n\nWe compute α with the ordinal difference function of Krippendorff [6], in which the disagreement between two ordinal ratings is a rank-based squared distance defined over the cumulative marginal category frequencies (not the raw squared difference (v1 − v2)^2, which is the interval metric). We use the reference krippendorff implementation. Values are reported in the main paper's Table 1 as the \"Krip. α\" column. We warn readers that on ceiling-effect dimensions the observed disagreement approaches the expected chance disagreement, driving α toward zero, or slightly negative, regardless of the high simple agreement on the same dimension.\n\n**D.2 Newcombe-Wilson hybrid CIs on recall difference**\n\nFor each (defect, dimension) cell we form the LALM recall p̂L = kL/n and human recall p̂H = kH/n, where kL and kH are the counts of perturbed clips where the respective judge's score drops by ≥ 1 point relative to baseline and n is the number of three-rater-covered perturbed clips for that cell. We compute the 95% CI on p̂L − p̂H using Newcombe's Method 10 (hybrid Wilson), which for two independent proportions combines the Wilson score CIs on each proportion into a lower bound L and upper bound U on the difference (see Newcombe [4], eqs. 12–14). A cell is flagged L>H when L > 0 and H>L when U < 0.\n\n**D.3 Paired-test robustness check**\n\nNewcombe's Method 10 treats the LALM and human recalls as two independent proportions, but they are in fact paired: both judges score the same perturbed clips. As a robustness check we re-tested each cell with an exact paired McNemar test on the per-clip discordant pairs (the clips one judge flags and the other does not). Under this stricter paired criterion, 2 of the 48 cells reach p < 0.05, both in the Human>LALM direction and both perfect 8-of-8-versus-0-of-8 splits: clip × audio_clarity and snr_noise × entity_pronunciation. The other five cells the Newcombe-Wilson intervals flagged do not survive the paired test at n ≤ 8: three of the five have a 5-of-5 (or 5-of-7) discordant split, i.e. every discordant pair favors the same judge, but at this sample size an exact binomial test needs a perfectly unanimous split to clear p < 0.05, so these read as underpowered directional misses rather than disconfirmed effects. This reinforces the main-text caution that the individual significant cells are hypotheses to confirm rather than established effects; only the two most extreme misses are robust to the paired analysis.\n\n**D.4 Bootstrap parameters**\n\nConfidence intervals on Spearman ρ between the LALM and each rater use non-parametric bootstrap with the following parameters:\n\n- Iterations: 1,000\n- Resampling unit: session (i.e. all 8 dimensions of a resampled session travel together)\n- Sampling: with replacement\n- CI method: percentile (2.5%, 97.5%)\n- Random seed: 42 (documented in the analysis script)\n\n**D.5 Human-human ρ confidence intervals**\n\nSection 4.1 compares the bootstrap 95% CI of the LALM-human ρ (Table 5) against the CI of the human-human ρ, which is not tabulated elsewhere in this paper. Table 14 reports it, computed with the identical session-level resampling procedure described above, applied to the average of the three pairwise rater-rater correlations. On 7 of 8 dimensions the two intervals overlap; on audio_clarity they do not, which is why that dimension's rank-correlation gap is treated as the one exception to the LALM-as-fourth-rater parity result. Source: rho_hh_ci.csv.\n\n**Table 14: Bootstrap 95% confidence intervals on the human-human ρ alongside the LALM-human ρ CI**\n\n| Dimension | ρHH | 95% CI (ρHH) | 95% CI (ρLH) | Overlap |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| accent_dialect_handling | +0.08 | [−0.01, +0.29] | [−0.12, +0.17] | yes |\n| audio_clarity | +0.47 | [+0.34, +0.58] | [+0.00, +0.30] | no |\n| speech_clarity | +0.01 | [−0.05, +0.08] | [+0.04, +0.33] | yes |\n| entity_pronunciation | +0.09 | [−0.00, +0.21] | [+0.04, +0.32] | yes |\n| prosody_naturalness | +0.11 | [+0.02, +0.20] | [+0.03, +0.28] | yes |\n| interruption_audio_quality | +0.25 | [+0.16, +0.34] | [+0.03, +0.29] | yes |\n| speaking_rate_adaptation | +0.17 | [+0.08, +0.26] | [+0.02, +0.26] | yes |\n| overall_fidelity | +0.11 | [+0.02, +0.20] | [−0.13, +0.15] | yes |\n\nBoth use the same 1,000-iteration, session-level, seed-42 procedure.\n\n**D.6 Pre-registration status**\n\nNone of the analyses in this paper were pre-registered. The three-regime taxonomy, the LALM-as-fourth-rater test, and the adversarial-defect design were specified before data collection. The persona-vs-codec decomposition and the per-rater-idiosyncrasy observation were identified post-hoc during analysis; the paper treats them as observational. The specific 0.07 rank-correlation-gap threshold used to report \"5 of 8 dimensions\" in Section 4.1 was likewise chosen after inspecting the data (it falls in an observed gap between the fifth- and sixth-closest dimensions, 0.07 versus 0.12) rather than fixed in advance; Table 5 reports the full per-dimension gaps so a reader can apply a different threshold if preferred.\n\n**E Reproducibility Manifest**\n\nAnalysis artefacts. Every table in this paper is derived from one of the thirteen CSV files listed below. File names refer to the layout of the supplementary archive that accompanies this paper on submission.\n\n| File | Sourced tables |\n|---|---|\n| h1_per_dim.csv | Tables 5, 9 |\n| h1_per_dim_natural.csv | Table 2 |\n| h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv | Table 6 |\n| h1_per_dim_gemini31propreview.csv | Table 7 |\n| cross_model_comparison.csv | Table 3 |\n| rho_hh_ci.csv | Table 14 |\n| lalm_as_4th_rater.csv | Table 5, Fig. 3 |\n| h2_per_config_per_dim.csv | Table 10 |\n| h3_defect_recall_with_ci.csv | Table 8, Fig. 4 |\n| e_ceiling_collapse.csv | Table 11 |\n| d_personality_vs_codec.csv | Table 12 |\n| full_per_session.csv | raw per-session ratings |\n| h3_defect_recall_3rater.csv | pre-CI defect counts |\n\nPrompt and schema source files. The LALM prompts (Appendix A.4) and their JSON schemas are reproduced verbatim from two production source files: speech_fidelity_prompt.py (AgentSpeechFidelity) and conversational_audio_quality.py (ConversationalAudioQuality). Both files are included in the supplementary archive.\n\nData availability. The anonymised CSVs, LALM prompts, JSON schemas, analysis scripts, and rendered figures described above are publicly available as a Hugging Face Dataset at https://huggingface.co/datasets/armaan-sayyad/lalm-judge-validation-full-duplex [7], released under CC-BY-4.0 for the data and figures and Apache License 2.0 for the scripts and prompts. Rater identifiers in the raw CSVs have been anonymised to R1, R2, R3 and session identifiers have been replaced with stable hashes. Every headline number in the paper can be reproduced from the released CSVs using the accompanying scripts. The 60 perturbed adversarial clips (short, derivative WAVs) will be included in a subsequent v0.2 release pending final data-clearance review. Raw session recordings from the primary 209-session corpus will not be publicly released, as they contain production agent output governed by internal data-handling policy. Requests for restricted access from bona fide researchers will be considered on a case-by-case basis.\n\n**F Notation Glossary**\n\n- LALM: Large Audio Language Model (Gemini 2.5 Flash in this study).\n- ρHH: pairwise human-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three rater pairs.\n- ρLH: LALM-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three (LALM, rater) pairs. Used in Appendix Table 5 and the LALM-as-fourth-rater comparison.\n- ρLH̄: Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating H̄ (a single series, not an average of pairwise correlations). Used for the per-stratum and score-region tables, where per-cell n is too small to average three pairwise correlations reliably.\n- H̄: across-rater mean of the three human ratings on a session × dimension.\n- % within 1: proportion of sessions where the two ratings being compared differ by at most 1 Likert point.\n- recall (adversarial arm): proportion of perturbed clips where the score drops by at least 1 point relative to the same clip's baseline rating.\n- L>H / H>L: significance flag on a (defect, dimension) cell where the LALM (respectively humans) are more sensitive under a Newcombe-Wilson 95% CI on the recall difference.\n\n---\n\nThat is the complete text of the paper, including all sections (1-8), all appendices (A-F), all 14 tables, all 4 figure descriptions, and all 11 references. The PDF was downloaded from https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.07985v1 (789 KB) and text was extracted using `pdftotext -layout`, yielding 1,234 lines / 82,605 characters of text.", "numLines": 274, "startLine": 400, "totalLines": 673}}}
